ed down after expiration of term''\n|-\n| [[Yemi Osinbajo]] (1957-)\n| [[Muhammadu Buhari]]\n| 29 May 2015\n| \u2013\n| [[All Progressives Congress]]\n| ''[[Incumbent]]''\n|}\n\n''*Chief of Staff, Supreme HQ; Chief of General Staff, Deputy Military Head of State, and de facto Vice President''\n\n==Post-vice presidency==\n\nThere are currently (since March 23, 2019) five living Vice Presidents of Nigeria since the first Vice President of Nigeria was appointed after the first military coup on January 15, 1966. \n\n* Former President [[Olusegun Obasanjo]] (1975-1976) under General [[Murtala Muhammad]] (age 82)\n* Former Vice President [[Ebitu Ukiwe]] (1985-1986) under General [[Ibrahim Babangida]] (age 79)\n* Former Vice President [[Oladipo Diya]] (1993-1997) under General [[Sani Abacha]] (age 74)\n* Former Vice President [[Atiku Abubakar]] (1999-2007) under President [[Olusegun Obasanjo]] (age 72)\n* Former President [[Goodluck Jonathan]] (2007-2010) under President [[Umaru Musa Yar'adua]] (age 61)\n* Former Vice President [[Namadi Sambo]] (2010-2015) under President [[Goodluck Ebele Jonathan]] (age 64)\n\n==See also==\n{{Portal|Nigeria|Politics}}\n*[[List of Governors-General of Nigeria]]\n*[[List of heads of state of Nigeria]]\n*[[List of heads of government of Nigeria]]\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{NigerianVicePresidents}}\n\n[[Category:Government of Nigeria]]\n[[Category:Lists of vice presidents|Nigeria]]\n[[Category:Vice Presidents of Nigeria| ]]\n[[Category:Lists of political office-holders in Nigeria|Vice President]]\n[[Category:1966 establishments in Nigeria]]\n\n{{Nigeria-gov-stub}}\n{{gov-job-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Cnwilliams", "label": "safe", "comment": "Disambiguated:National Economic Council\u2192National Economic Council (Nigeria)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Vice_President_of_Nigeria"}
{"title_page": "Birgit Minichmayr", "text_new": "{{short description|Austrian actress born in Linz, Austria|bot=PearBOT 5}}\n{{no footnotes|date=March 2013}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=September 2016}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name         = Birgit Minichmayr\n| image        = Birgit Minichmayr, ROMY 2009.jpg\n| imagesize    = 220px\n| caption        = Minichmayr in 2009\n| birth_date   = {{birth date and age|1977|4|3|df=y}}\n| birth_place  = [[Linz]], [[Austria]]\n}}\n\n'''Birgit Minichmayr''' (born 3 April 1977)<ref>{{cite news |last= |first= |date=13 February 2019 |title=Birgit Minichmayr erh\u00e4lt Gro\u00dfen Schauspielpreis der Diagonale |url=https://www.derstandard.de/story/2000097955180/diagonale-birgit-minichmayr-erhaelt-grossen-schauspielpreis |work=[[Der Standard]] |location=Vienna |agency=APA |access-date=14 October 2019}}</ref> is an [[Austrians|Austrian]] actress born in [[Linz]], [[Austria]]. She studied drama at the [[Max Reinhardt Seminar]] in [[Vienna]].<ref>{{cite news |last=Wewer |first=A. |date=17 May 2010 |title=\"Ich w\u00e4re gerne anders\" |url=https://www.sueddeutsche.de/kultur/birgit-minichmayr-ueber-liebe-ich-waere-gerne-anders-1.447104 |work=[[S\u00fcddeutsche Zeitung]] |location=Munich |language=de |access-date=14 October 2019}}</ref> For her work in [[Maren Ade]]'s film [[Everyone Else]] she won [[Silver Bear for Best Actress]] at [[59th Berlin International Film Festival]]. She is the only Austrian actress to win this award in history of the festival and the first Austrian actress to win best actress award at a major European film festival ([[Cannes film festival|Cannes]], [[Venice film festival|Venice]], [[Berlin film festival|Berlin]]) since 1956. She worked with several major European directors including [[Michael Haneke]], [[Tom Tykwer]] and [[Jessica Hausner]].\n\n==Career==\nMinichmayr had her first break with the [[Burgtheater]] in [[Vienna]], where she appeared in numerous plays, including ''Der Reigen'' by [[Arthur Schnitzler]] (staged by [[Sven-Eric Bechtolf]]), ''Troilus and Cressida'' by [[William Shakespeare]] (staging by [[Declan Donnellan]]) and ''Der F\u00e4rber und sein Zwillingsbruder'' by [[Johann Nestroy]] (staged by [[Karlheinz Hackl]]). She made her cinema debut in 2000 as Barbara Brecht in [[Jan Sch\u00fctte]]'s ''[[The Farewell (2000 film)|Abschied]]'', playing alongside [[Josef Bierbichler]] and [[Monica Bleibtreu]]. In 2000,  Minichmayr appeared in [[Peter S\u00e4mann]]'s television thriller (in the ''[[Tatort]]'' series), \"B\u00f6ses Blut\". She was awarded the [[Austria]]n [[Nestroy Theatre Prize|Nestroy Prize]] for \"Best Young Talent\" in 2000. In 2006 she played [[Mizzi Kasper]], one of the lovers from [[Rudolf, Crown Prince of Austria|Crownprince Rudolf]] in the movie ''{{Interlanguage link multi|Kronprinz Rudolfs letzte Liebe (2006)|de|3=Kronprinz Rudolfs letzte Liebe (2006)|lt=Kronprinz Rudolfs letzte Liebe}}''. A year later, Minichmayr played the fool in [[Luc Bondy]]'s acclaimed staging of Shakespeare's ''[[King Lear]]'', always at the Burgtheater.\n\nMinichmayr currently lives in [[Munich]] and Vienna. She speaks [[English language|English]] and has acted in several international and English language productions. Among the directors she worked with were [[Istv\u00e1n Szab\u00f3]], [[G\u00f6tz Spielmann]], [[Tom Tykwer]], [[Oliver Hirschbiegel]], [[Robert Dornhelm]], and [[Doris D\u00f6rrie]].  She is also an accomplished vocalist, and has been recorded several times, though she has always made acting her primary focus.\n\nAt the [[59th Berlin International Film Festival]] 2009 Minichmayr was awarded the [[Silver Bear for Best Actress]] for her performance in [[Maren Ade]]'s ''Alle Anderen'' ([[Everyone Else]]).\n\n==Filmography==\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n| '''Date'''\n| '''Film'''\n| '''Role'''\n| '''Director'''\n| '''Notes'''\n|-\n| 2000\n| ''[[The Farewell (2000 film)|Abschied]]''\n| Barbara Brecht\n| [[Jan Sch\u00fctte]]\n|\n|-\n| 2000\n| ''[[Tatort]] - B\u00f6ses Blut''\n| Kathi\n| [[Peter S\u00e4mann]]\n| TV film - Awarded [[Nestroy Theatre Prize|Nestroy Prize]] for ''Best Young Talent''\n|-\n| 2001\n| ''[[Taking Sides (film)|Taking Sides]]''\n| Emmi Straube\n| [[Istv\u00e1n Szab\u00f3]]\n|\n|-\n| 2001\n| ''[[Spiel im Morgengrauen]]''\n| Steffi\n| [[G\u00f6tz Spielmann]]\n| TV film\n|-\n| 2002\n| ''[[Liegen Lernen]]''\n| Tina\n| [[Hendrik Handloeghten]]\n|\n|-\n| 2004\n| ''[[Hotel (2004 film)|Hotel]]''\n| Petra\n| [[Jessica Hausner]]\n|\n|-\n| 2004\n| ''[[Downfall (2004 film)|Downfall]]''\n| [[Gerda Christian]]\n| [[Oliver Hirschbiegel]]\n|\n|-\n| 2004\n| ''[[Spiele Leben]]''\n| Tanja\n| [[Antonin Svoboda (director)|Antonin Svoboda]]\n|\n|-\n| 2004\n| ''[[Daniel K\u00e4fer]] - Die Villen der Frau H\u00fcrsch''\n| Mirz Schl\u00f6mmer\n| [[Julian P\u00f6lsner]]\n| TV film\n|-\n| 2005\n| ''[[Perfume: The Story of a Murderer]]''\n| Grenouille's Mother\n| [[Tom Tykwer]]\n|\n|-\n| 2005\n| ''[[Fallen (2005 film)|Fallen]]''\n| Brigitte\n| [[Barbara Albert]]\n|\n|-\n| 2006\n| ''[[Krankheit der Jugend]]''\n| \n| Students of [[Michael Haneke]]\n|\n|-\n| 2006\n| ''{{Interlanguage link multi|Kronprinz Rudolfs letzte Liebe (2006)|de|3=Kronprinz Rudolfs letzte Liebe (2006)|lt=Kronprinz Rudolfs letzte Liebe}}''\n| [[Mizzi Kasper]]\n| [[Robert Dornhelm]]\n| TV film\n|-\n| 2006\n| ''[[Polizeiruf 110]] - Kellers Kind''\n| Aglaia\n| [[Titus Selge]]\n| TV film\n|-\n| 2007\n| ''[[Midsummer Madness (2007 film)|Midsummer Madness]]'' \n| Maja\n| [[Alexander Hahn (film director)|Alexander Hahn]]\n|\n|-\n| 2008\n| ''[[Cherry Blossoms (film)|Kirschbl\u00fcten - Hanami]]''\n| Karolin Angermeier  \n| [[Doris D\u00f6rrie]]\n|\n|-\n| 2009\n| ''[[Der Knochenmann]]''\n| Birgit\n| [[Wolfgang Murnberger]]\n|\n|-\n| 2009\n| ''[[The White Ribbon]]''\n| Frieda\n| [[Michael Haneke]]\n|\n|-\n| 2009\n| ''[[Everyone Else]]''\n| Gitti\n| [[Maren Ade]]\n|\n|-\n| 2012\n| ''[[Mercy (2012 film)|Mercy]]''\n| Maria\n| [[Matthias Glasner]]\n|\n|-\n|2015\n|''[[Jack (2015 film)|Jack]]''\n|\n|\n|\n|-\n|2017\n|''[[Animals (2017 film)|Animals]]''\n|\n|\n|\n|-\n|}\n\n==Awards==\n* 2000: [[Nestroy Theatre Prize|Nestroy Prize]] for Best Young Talent\n* 2004/2009: Nestroy Prize for Best Actress<ref>{{cite news |last= |first= |date=21 November 2004 |title=\"Nestroy\"-Preis an Toni Slama und Birgit Minichmayr |url=https://www.derstandard.at/story/1865533/nestroy-preis-an-toni-slama-und-birgit-minichmayr |work=[[Der Standard]] |location=Vienna |access-date=13 October 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last= |first= |date=12 October 2009 |title=Nestroy: Birgit Minichmayr r\u00e4umt doppelt ab |url=https://www.diepresse.com/514596/nestroy-birgit-minichmayr-raumt-doppelt-ab |work=[[Die Presse]] |location=Vienna |access-date=13 October 2019}}</ref>\n* 2009: 59th Berlin International Film Festival, Best Actress for [[Everyone Else]]\n* 2010: German Film Awards, Nomination Best Actress for [[Everyone Else]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{IMDb name|0591352}}\n\n{{Silver Bear for Best Actress}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Minichmayr, Birgit}}\n[[Category:Austrian film actresses]]\n[[Category:1977 births]]\n[[Category:People from Linz]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Shakespearean actresses]]\n[[Category:Austrian stage actresses]]\n[[Category:Silver Bear for Best Actress winners]]\n[[Category:21st-century Austrian actresses]]\n[[Category:Austrian female singers]]\n[[Category:Austrian television actresses]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Austrian actress born in Linz, Austria|bot=PearBOT 5}}\n{{no footnotes|date=March 2013}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=September 2016}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name         = Birgit Minichmayr\n| image        = Birgit Minichmayr, ROMY 2009.jpg\n| imagesize    = 220px\n| caption        = Minichmayr in 2009\n| birth_date   = {{birth date and age|1977|4|3|df=y}}\n| birth_place  = [[Linz]], [[Austria]]\n}}\n\n'''Birgit Minichmayr''' (born 3 April 1977)<ref>{{cite news |last= |first= |date=13 February 2019 |title=Birgit Minichmayr erh\u00e4lt Gro\u00dfen Schauspielpreis der Diagonale |url=https://www.derstandard.de/story/2000097955180/diagonale-birgit-minichmayr-erhaelt-grossen-schauspielpreis |work=[[Der Standard]] |location=Vienna |agency=APA |access-date=14 October 2019}}</ref> is an [[Austrians|Austrian]] actress born in [[Linz]], [[Austria]]. She studied drama at the [[Max Reinhardt Seminar]] in [[Vienna]].<ref>{{cite news |last=Wewer |first=A. |date=17 May 2010 |title=\"Ich w\u00e4re gerne anders\" |url=https://www.sueddeutsche.de/kultur/birgit-minichmayr-ueber-liebe-ich-waere-gerne-anders-1.447104 |work=[[S\u00fcddeutsche Zeitung]] |location=Munich |language=de |access-date=14 October 2019}}</ref> For her work in [[Maren Ade]]'s film [[Everyone Else]] she won [[Silver Bear for Best Actress]] at [[59th Berlin International Film Festival]]. She is the only Austrian actress to win this award in history of the festival and the first Austrian actress to win best actress award at a major European film festival ([[Cannes film festival|Cannes]], [[Venice film festival|Venice]], [[Berlin film festival|Berlin]]) since 1956. She worked with several major European directors including [[Michael Haneke]], [[Tom Tykwer]] and [[Jessica Hausner]].\n\n==Career==\nMinichmayr had her first break with the [[Burgtheater]] in [[Vienna]], where she appeared in numerous plays, including ''Der Reigen'' by [[Arthur Schnitzler]] (staged by [[Sven-Eric Bechtolf]]), ''Troilus and Cressida'' by [[William Shakespeare]] (staging by [[Declan Donnellan]]) and ''Der F\u00e4rber und sein Zwillingsbruder'' by [[Johann Nestroy]] (staged by [[Karlheinz Hackl]]). She made her cinema debut in 2000 as Barbara Brecht in [[Jan Sch\u00fctte]]'s ''[[The Farewell (2000 film)|Abschied]]'', playing alongside [[Josef Bierbichler]] and [[Monica Bleibtreu]]. In 2000,  Minichmayr appeared in [[Peter S\u00e4mann]]'s television thriller (in the ''[[Tatort]]'' series), \"B\u00f6ses Blut\". She was awarded the [[Austria]]n [[Nestroy Theatre Prize|Nestroy Prize]] for \"Best Young Talent\" in 2000. In 2006 she played [[Mizzi Kasper]], one of the lovers from [[Rudolf, Crown Prince of Austria|Crownprince Rudolf]] in the movie ''{{Interlanguage link multi|Kronprinz Rudolfs letzte Liebe (2006)|de|3=Kronprinz Rudolfs letzte Liebe (2006)|lt=Kronprinz Rudolfs letzte Liebe}}''. A year later, Minichmayr played the fool in [[Luc Bondy]]'s acclaimed staging of Shakespeare's ''[[King Lear]]'', always at the Burgtheater.\n\nMinichmayr currently lives in [[Munich]] and Vienna. She speaks [[English language|English]] and has acted in several international and English language productions. Among the directors she worked with were [[Istv\u00e1n Szab\u00f3]], [[G\u00f6tz Spielmann]], [[Tom Tykwer]], [[Oliver Hirschbiegel]], [[Robert Dornhelm]], and [[Doris D\u00f6rrie]].  She is also an accomplished vocalist, and has been recorded several times, though she has always made acting her primary focus.\n\nAt the [[59th Berlin International Film Festival]] 2009 Minichmayr was awarded the [[Silver Bear for Best Actress]] for her performance in [[Maren Ade]]'s ''Alle Anderen'' ([[Everyone Else]]).\n\n==Filmography==\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n| '''Date'''\n| '''Film'''\n| '''Role'''\n| '''Director'''\n| '''Notes'''\n|-\n| 2000\n| ''[[The Farewell (2000 film)|Abschied]]''\n| Barbara Brecht\n| [[Jan Sch\u00fctte]]\n|\n|-\n| 2000\n| ''[[Tatort]] - B\u00f6ses Blut''\n| Kathi\n| [[Peter S\u00e4mann]]\n| TV film - Awarded [[Nestroy Theatre Prize|Nestroy Prize]] for ''Best Young Talent''\n|-\n| 2001\n| ''[[Taking Sides (film)|Taking Sides]]''\n| Emmi Straube\n| [[Istv\u00e1n Szab\u00f3]]\n|\n|-\n| 2001\n| ''[[Spiel im Morgengrauen]]''\n| Steffi\n| [[G\u00f6tz Spielmann]]\n| TV film\n|-\n| 2002\n| ''[[Liegen Lernen]]''\n| Tina\n| [[Hendrik Handloeghten]]\n|\n|-\n| 2004\n| ''[[Hotel (2004 film)|Hotel]]''\n| Petra\n| [[Jessica Hausner]]\n|\n|-\n| 2004\n| ''[[Downfall (2004 film)|Downfall]]'