water\n| first = Daniel\n| title = The Revenge of Pinkwater\n| work = The Washington Post\n| date = 1987-11-08\n| url = https://pqasb.pqarchiver.com/washingtonpost_historical/access/136245482.html?FMT=ABS\n}}\n*{{Cite news\n| last = Waldrop\n| first = Howard\n| title = Daniel Pinkwater Weighs In\n| work = The Washington Post\n| date = 1989-10-01\n| url = https://pqasb.pqarchiver.com/washingtonpost/access/73901927.html?FMT=ABS\n}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Portal|Children's literature}}\n*[http://www.pinkwater.com/ Pinkwater's Official site]\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20060709050417/http://www.pinkwater.com/pzone/ The P-Zone: Unofficial Pinkwater Site]\n*{{IMDb name|id=0684414|name=Daniel M. Pinkwater}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Pinkwater, Daniel}}\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:1941 births]]\n[[Category:Bard College alumni]]\n[[Category:Jewish American writers]]\n[[Category:American children's writers]]\n[[Category:American male writers]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox writer\n| name          = Daniel Pinkwater\n| image         = Daniel Pinkwater 2011.jpg\n| image_size    = \n| alt           = \n| caption       = Pinkwater in 2011\n| pseudonym     = Daniel Pinkwater, Daniel M. Pinkwater, Daniel Manus Pinkwater, D. Manus Pinkwater\n| birth_name    = \n| birth_date    = {{birth date and age|1941|11|15}}\n| birth_place   = [[Memphis, Tennessee]]\n| death_date    = <!-- {{Death date and age|YYYY|MM|DD|YYYY|MM|DD}} -->\n| death_place   = \n| resting_place = \n| occupation    = Author, illustrator\n| language      = \n| nationality   = American\n| ethnicity     = \n| citizenship   = \n| education     = \n| alma_mater    = [[Bard College]]\n| period        = \n| genre         = [[Children's literature]], young adult fiction\n| subject       = \n| movement      = \n| notableworks  = ''[[The Snarkout Boys and the Avocado of Death]]'', ''[[The Big Orange Splot]]'', ''[[Borgel]]''\n| spouse        = Jill Pinkwater \n| partner       = \n| children      = \n| relatives     = \n| awards        = \n| signature     = \n| signature_alt = \n| website       = {{URL|http://pinkwater.com/}}\n| portaldisp    = \n}}\n\n'''Daniel Manus Pinkwater''' (born November 15, 1941) is an American author of [[Children's literature|children's books]] and [[young adult fiction]]. His books include ''Lizard Music'', ''The Snarkout Boys and the Avocado of Death'', ''Fat Men from Space'', ''[[Borgel]]'', and the picture book ''[[The Big Orange Splot]]''. He has also written an adult novel, ''The Afterlife Diet'', and essay collections derived from his talks on [[National Public Radio]].\n\nMany elements of his fiction are based on real events and people he encountered in his youth.\n\nPinkwater is a trained artist and has illustrated many of his books, but for more recent works, that task has passed to his wife, Jill Pinkwater. His artistic technique varies from work to work, with some books illustrated in computer drawings, others in woodcuts and others in Magic Marker.\n\nPinkwater varies his name slightly between books (for instance, \"Daniel Pinkwater\", \"Daniel M. Pinkwater\", \"Daniel Manus Pinkwater\", \"D. Manus Pinkwater\").\n\nHe was born in [[Memphis, Tennessee]], to [[Judaism|Jewish]] immigrant parents from [[Poland]].  He describes his father as a \"ham-eating, iconoclastic Jew.\" His parents moved to [[Chicago]], where he grew up. He attended [[Bard College]].\n\n==Themes==\nPinkwater tends to write about social misfits who find themselves in bizarre situations, such as searching for a floating island populated by human-sized intelligent lizards (''Lizard Music''), exploring other universes with an obscure relative (''[[Borgel]]''), or discovering that their teeth can function as interstellar [[radio]] antennae (''Fat Men from Space'').  They are often, though not always, set in thinly\u2014or not at all\u2014disguised versions of Chicago and [[Hoboken, New Jersey]].  He often includes Chicago landmarks and folkloric figures from his childhood in 1950s Chicago, regardless of when the book is set. An example of this is the recurring character the Chicken Man, a mysterious but dignified black man who carries a performing chicken on his head.  This character is based on a shadowy figure from 1950s Chicago; after Pinkwater made him a lead character in ''Lizard Music'' he received letters from Chicago residents who remembered the Chicken Man.  Pinkwater also pays tribute to the Clark Theater (a repertory movie theatre on Clark Street in the [[Chicago Loop]] that changed features daily and stayed open all night), [[Bughouse Square]], and Ed & Fred's Red Hots.  Another common theme is Jewish culture, with characters incongruously speaking in [[Yiddish]]-influenced dialogue or participating in [[Borscht Belt]] culture. Characters sometimes have surnames that append the \"-stein\" element familiar in some Jewish names to names suggesting other ethnicities (e.g., \"Wentworthstein\").\n\nIn 1995, Pinkwater published his first adult novel, ''The Afterlife Diet'', in which a mediocre editor, upon dying, finds himself in a tacky [[Catskills]] resort populated by \"circumferentially challenged\" deceased.\n\n==Comics and radio==\nPinkwater authored the newspaper comic strip ''[[Norb (comic)|Norb]]'', which was illustrated by [[Tony Auth]].  The strip, syndicated by [[King Features]], was cancelled after 52 weeks.<ref>\n[http://www.toonopedia.com/norb.htm Norb] ''Don Markstein's Toonopedia'',  accessed on May 10, 2007.</ref>  The daily strips were released in a 78-page collection by [[MU Press]] in 1992.\n\nPinkwater is also a longtime commentator on [[National Public Radio]].  He regularly reviews children's books on NPR's ''Weekend Edition Saturday''.  For several years, he had his own NPR show: ''Chinwag Theater''.  Pinkwater is also known to avid fans of the NPR radio show ''[[Car Talk]]'', where he has appeared as a (seemingly) random caller, commenting, for example, on the physics of the buttocks (giving rise to the proposed unit of measure of seat size: the Pinkwater), and giving practical advice as to the choice of [[automobile]]s.  In the early 1990s Pinkwater voiced a series of humorous radio advertisements for the Ford Motor Company.\n\n==Challenged book==\nFollowing an appearance by Pinkwater on the [[Public Radio International]] program ''[[This American Life]]'',<ref>[http://www.thisamericanlife.org/radio-archives/episode/43/faustian-bargains?act=4 This American Life episode #43: Faustian Bargains], broadcast 22 November 1996. ([http://www.thisamericanlife.org/radio-archives/episode/43/transcript transcript])</ref> his book ''The Devil in the Drain'' ended up on [[Challenge (literature)|challenged]] book lists at numerous children's libraries.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.uwplatt.edu/swal/Conference/Fall04Conference.htm|title=Fall 2004 SWAL Conference Information|publisher=Southwest Wisconsin Association of Libraries Conferences|accessdate=29 January 2011|archiveurl=http://webcache.googleusercontent.com/search?q=cache:gH6veCPSR8gJ:www.uwplatt.edu/swal/Conferences/Fall04Conference.htm+http://www.uwplatt.edu/swal/Conference/Fall04Conference.htm&cd=1&hl=en&ct=clnk&gl=us&client=firefox-a|archivedate=Jan 15, 2011}}</ref><!-- This is incorrect!  The source does not indicate that the ban followed the appearance on This American Life -- and in the episode itself, it is mentioned at the end of the on-air reading of it that \"Daniel Pinkwater's book, Devil in the Drain, has been banned by children's libraries all over America. Really.\"  It is possible that the episode brought the book to the attention of some people and it was *newly* banned in places -- but again, the source given does not indicate this. -->\n\n==''The Hare and the Pineapple'' used on exams==\nIn April 2012, a story attributed to Daniel Pinkwater, \"The Hare and the Pineapple\", was used on a standardized exam for 8th grade students in [[New York (city)|New York]]. The story was based on Pinkwater's short story, \"The Story of the Rabbit and the Eggplant\", which he had sold to the testing company.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.pinkwater.com/pzone/ |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2006-07-07 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20060709050417/http://www.pinkwater.com/pzone/ |archivedate=2006-07-09 }}</ref>  The published version changed the racer from an eggplant to a pineapple, and changed the moral of the story.<ref>{{cite web|last=McGrath |first=Ben |url=http://www.newyorker.com/talk/2012/05/07/120507ta_talk_mcgrath |title=Daniel Pinkwater on \"The Hare and the Pineapple\" |publisher=The New Yorker |date= |accessdate=2012-06-05}}</ref> Students were asked two perplexing questions: \"Why did the animals eat the pineapple?\" and \"Which animal spoke the wisest words?\"<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.nydailynews.com/new-york/talking-pineapple-question-state-exam-stumps-article-1.1064657#ixzz1t3HvMvSp |title=Talking pineapple question on state exam stumps ... everyone! |publisher=NY Daily News |date=2012-04-19 |accessdate=2012-06-05 |location=New York |first1=Ben |last1=Chapman |first2=Rachel |last2=Monahan}}</ref> These questions baffled students.<ref>{{cite news|last=Strauss |first=Valerie |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/blogs/answer-sheet/post/talking-pineapple-question-on-standardized-test-baffles-students/2012/04/20/gIQA8i01VT_blog.html |title=\u2018Talking pineapple\u2019 question on standardized test baffles students - The Answer Sheet |publisher=The Washington Post |date=2012-04-20 |accessdate=2012-06-05}}</ref> City Schools Chancellor [[Dennis Walcott]] issued a statement saying improvements on the state exam will be made in the future.<ref>{{cite news|author=04/20/2012 1:47 pm Updated: 04/25/2012 3:26 pm |url=http://www.huffingtonpost.com/2012/04/20/ridiculous-talking-pineapple-question-on-state-exam_n_1440942.html |title=Talking Pineapple Question On 8th-Grade New York State Exam Confuses Everyone (UPDATE) |publisher=Huffingtonpost.com |date= 2012-04-20|accessdate=2012-06-05}}</ref> The ''[[New York Daily News]]'' staff sent the question to ''[[Jeopardy!]]'' champion [[Ken Jennings]], and he was stumped as well.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://now.msn.com/now/0420-pineapple-test-question.aspx |title='Talking pineapple' questions confuse kids, teachers, world |publisher=Now.msn.com |accessdate=2012-06-05 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120422172302/http://now.msn.com/now/0420-pineapple-test-question.aspx |archivedate=2012-04-22 }}</ref>\n\n==Partial bibliography==\n\n===Children's books===\n* ''The Terrible Roar'' (1970)\n* ''Bear's Picture'' (1972)\n* ''Wizard Crystal'' (1973)\n* ''Fat Elliot and the Gorilla'' (1974)\n* ''Magic Camera'' (1974)\n* ''Blue Moose'' (1975)\n* ''Three Big Hogs'' (1975)\n* ''Around Fred's Bed'' (1976)\n* ''[[The Big Orange Splot]]'' (1977)\n* ''The Blue Thing'' (1977)\n* ''Fat Men From Space'' (1977)\n* ''Pickle Creature'' (1979)\n* ''Return of the Moose'' (1979)\n* ''The Magic Moscow'' (1980)\n* ''The Wuggie Norple Story'' (1980)\n* ''Attila the Pun: A Magic Moscow Story'' (1981)\n* ''Roger's Umbrella'' (1981)\n* ''Tooth-Gnasher Superflash'' (1981)\n* ''[[Slaves of Spiegel]]: A Magic Moscow Story'' (1982)\n* ''I Was a Second Grade Werewolf'' (1983)\n* ''Devil in the Drain'' (1984)\n* ''Ducks!'' (1984)\n* ''Jolly Roger: A Dog of Hoboken'' (1985)\n* ''The Frankenbagel Monster'' (1986)\n* ''The Moosepire'' (1986)\n* ''The Muffin Fiend'' (1986)\n* ''Aunt Lulu'' (1988)\n* ''Guys from Space'' (1989)\n* ''Uncle Melvin'' (1989)\n* ''Doodle Flute'' (1991)\n* ''Wempires'' (1991)\n* ''The Phantom of the Lunch Wagon'' (1992)\n* ''Author's Day'' (1993)\n* ''Spaceburger: A Keven Spoon and Mason Mintz Story'' (1993)\n* ''Ned Feldman, Space Pirate'' (1994)\n* ''Mush, A Dog from Space'' (1995)\n* ''Goose Night'' (1996), later reprinted as ''The Magic Goose'' (1997)\n* ''Wallpaper from Space'' (1997)\n* ''At the Hotel Larry'' (1998)\n* ''Young Larry'' (1998)\n* ''Bongo Larry'' (1998)\n* ''Second Grade Ape'' (1998)\n* ''Wolf Christmas'' (1999)\n* ''Big Bob and the Halloween Potatoes'' (1999)\n* ''Big Bob and the Magic Valentine's Day Potato'' (1999)\n* ''Big Bob and the Holiday Potato'' (1999)\n* ''Rainy Morning'' (2000)\n* ''Ice Cream Larry'' (2000)\n* ''Sleepover Larry'' (2000)\n* ''Bad Bears Go Visiting: An Irving and Muktuk Story'' (2000)\n* ''Big Bob and the Thanksgiving Potatoes'' (2000)\n* ''The Werewolf Club #1: The Magic Pretzel'' (2001)\n* ''The Werewolf Club #2: The Lunchroom of Doom'' (2001)\n* ''Cone Kong: The Scary Ice Cream Giant'' (2001)\n* ''Fat Camp Commandos'' (2001)\n* ''Irving and Muktuk: Two Bad Bears'' (2002)\n* ''The Werewolf Club #3: The Werewolf Club Meets Dorkula'' (2002)\n* ''The Werewolf Club #4: The Werewolf Club Meets the Hound of the Basketballs'' (2002)\n* ''Fat Camp Commandos Go West'' (2003)\n* ''Mush's Jazz Adventure'' (2004)\n* ''The Werewolf Club #5: The Werewolf Club Meets Oliver Twit'' (2005)\n* ''Bad Bears in the Big City: An Irving and Muktuk Story'' (2005)\n* ''The Picture of Morty and Ray'' (2006)\n* ''Bad Bears and a Bunny: An Irving and Muktuk Story'' (2006)\n* ''Bad Bear Detectives: An Irving and Muktuk Story'' (2007)\n* ''Dancing Larry'' (2007)\n* ''Yo-Yo Man'' (2007)\n* ''Beautiful Yetta: The Yiddish Chicken'' (2010)\n* ''I Am the Dog'' (2010)\n* ''Mrs. Noodlekugel'' (2012)\n* ''Beautiful Yetta's Hanukkah Kitten'' (2014)\n\n===Young adult/Teen novels===\n* ''Wingman'' (1975)\n* ''Lizard Music'' (1976)\n* ''[[The Hoboken Chicken Emergency]]'' (1977)\n* ''The Last Guru'' (1978)\n* ''[[Alan Mendelsohn, the Boy from Mars|Alan Mendelsohn, Boy From Mars]]'' (1979)\n* ''[[Yobgorgle: Mystery Monster of Lake Ontario]]'' (1979)\n* ''[[The Worms of Kukumlima]]'' (1981)\n* ''[[The Snarkout Boys and the Avocado of Death]]'' (1982)\n* ''Young Adult Novel'' (1982)\n* ''The Snarkout Boys and the Baconburg Horror'' (1984)\n* ''[[Borgel]]'' (1990) aka ''The Time Tourists'' (1993) [UK]\n* ''[[The Education of Robert Nifkin]]'' (1999)\n* ''The Neddiad : How Neddie Took the Train, Went to Hollywood, and Saved Civilization'' (2006)\n* ''The Yggysey'' (2008)\n* ''The Adventures of a Cat-Whiskered Girl'' (2010)\n* ''Bushman Lives''<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.bushmanlives.com/sample-page/ |title=Bushman Lives -- About the Book |accessdate=2011-09-14 |url-status=bot: unknown |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110930195756/http://www.bushmanlives.com/sample-page/ |archivedate=September 30, 2011 }}</ref> (October 2012)\n* ''Escape to Dwerg Mountain''<ref>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=aHAYS9MxSPgC&pg=PT286 |title=mention of sequel on the last page of '&#39;The Adventures of a Cat-Whiskered Girl'&#39; |publisher=Books.google.com |date= |accessdate=2012-06-05}}</ref> (TBA)\n\n====Collections====\n* ''Young Adults'' (1991)\n** contains ''Young Adult Novel'', the stories ''Dead End Dada'' and ''The Dada Boys in Collitch'' (not printed elsewhere), and some Kevin Shapiro stories sent in to the author by fans.\n* ''5 Novels'' (1997)\n** collects ''Alan Mendelsohn, the Boy from Mars''; ''Slaves of Spiegel''; ''The Last Guru''; ''Young Adult Novel''; ''The Snarkout Boys and the Avocado of Death''\n* ''4 Fantastic Novels'' (2000)\n** collects ''Borgel'', ''Yobgorgle'', ''The Worms of Kukumlima'', ''The Snarkout Boys & the Baconburg Horror''\n* ''Once Upon a Blue Moose'' (2006)\n** collects ''Blue Moose'', ''Return of the Moose'', and ''The Moosepire''\n\n===Adult fiction===\n* ''The Afterlife Diet'' (1995)\n\n===Non-fiction===\n* ''Hoboken Fish and Chicago Whistle'' (1999): a book of essays, combining essays from two previous books:\n** ''Chicago Days, Hoboken Nights'' (1991)\n** ''Fish Whistle'' (1989)\n* ''Superpuppy: How to Choose, Raise, and Train the Best Possible Dog for You'' (1977)\n* ''Uncle Boris in the Yukon and Other Shaggy Dog Stories'' (2001)\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n*\"Daniel Manus Pinkwater\". Entry in \"Contemporary Authors Online\", Thomson Gale, 2005. Accessed 2005-09-27.\n\n==Further reading==\n*{{cite book|last=Hogan|first=Walter|title=The Agony and the Eggplant: Daniel Pinkwater's Heroic Struggles in the Name of YA Literature|year=2001|publisher=Scarecrow Press|location=Lanham, Md [u.a.]|isbn=9780810839946|url=https://archive.org/details/agonyeggplantdan00hoga}}\n*{{cite news |first=Josh |last=Nathan-Kazis |url=http://forward.com/articles/206667/how-daniel-pinkwater-became-my-own-personal-guru/ |title=How Daniel Pinkwater Became My Own Personal Guru |newspaper=[[The Jewish Daily Forward]] |date=10 October 2014}}\n*{{cite book|last=McGinty|first=Alice B.|title=Meet Daniel Pinkwater|year=2003|publisher=Powerkids Press|location=New York|isbn=9780823964062|url=https://archive.org/details/meetdanielpinkwa00mcgi}}\n*{{Cite news\n| last = Pinkwater\n| first = Daniel\n| title = The Revenge of Pinkwater\n| work = The Washington Post\n| date = 1987-11-08\n| url = https://pqasb.pqarchiver.com/washingtonpost_historical/access/136245482.html?FMT=ABS\n}}\n*{{Cite news\n| last = Waldrop\n| first = Howard\n| title = Daniel Pinkwater Weighs In\n| work = The Washington Post\n| date = 1989-10-01\n| url = https://pqasb.pqarchiver.com/washingtonpost/access/73901927.html?FMT=ABS\n}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Portal|Children's literature}}\n*[http://www.pinkwater.com/ Pinkwater's Official site]\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20060709050417/http://www.pinkwater.com/pzone/ The P-Zone: Unofficial Pinkwater Site]\n*{{IMDb name|id=0684414|name=Daniel M. Pinkwater}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Pinkwater, Daniel}}\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:1941 births]]\n[[Category:Bard College alumni]]\n[[Category:Jewish American writers]]\n[[Category:American children's writers]]\n[[Category:American male writers]]\n", "name_user": "Jessyrandall", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eYoung adult/Teen novels:moved two titles from children's to YA", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Daniel_Pinkwater"}
{"title_page": "Tamar Hematite Iron Company", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date = March 2012}}\n\n{{Use Australian English|date = March 2012}}\n\nThe '''Tamar Hematite Iron Company''' (THIC) was an iron mining and smelting company that operated from April 1874 to December 1877, in the area close to the location of the modern-day township of [[Beaconsfield, Tasmania|Beaconsfield]],[[Tasmania]], Australia.\n\nThe company's operations consisted of an iron ore mine near Brandy Creek, a blast furnace, jetty and township, on the Middle Arm of the estuary of the [[Kanamaluka / Tamar River|Tamar River]], a tramway connecting the two sites, and charcoal and brick kilns. \n\nThe THIC was the first company to produce iron in commercial quantities from Tasmanian ore and bring their product to market, although others had made small quantities earlier.<ref name=\":12\">{{Cite news|url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article66072629|title=TAMAR HEMATITE IRON COMPANY|last=|first=|date=1875-01-04|work=Cornwall Chronicle (Launceston, Tas. : 1835 - 1880)|access-date=2019-10-09|pages=2}}</ref> It was the second company in Australia\u2014at the time considered to be six separate self-governing British colonies\u2014to make commercial quantities of pig-iron that was smelted from Australian iron ore.<ref name=\":192\">{{Cite book|title=Furnace, fire & forge : Lithgow's iron and steel industry, 1874\u20131932|last=McKillop, Robert F.|date=2006|publisher=Light Railway Research Society of Australia|others=Light Railway Research Society of Australia.|isbn=0909340447|location=Melbourne, Australia|pages=16, 17|oclc=156757606}}</ref><ref name=\":110\">{{Cite book|title=The Lal Lal Blast Furnace Reserve report|last=Staughton|first=Peter Samuel|date=1976|publisher=[National Trust of Australia, Victoria]|others=Ashley, Robert William P.,, National Trust of Australia (Vic.), Lal Lal Blast Furnace Reserve. Committee of Management.|isbn=090971018X|location=[South Yarra, Vic.]|pages=124|oclc=27604498}}</ref>\n\n[[Pig iron|Pig-iron]] of good quality was made in its blast furnace from January 1875, until July 1875 when operations were suspended. Complicated by a decline in the price of pig iron, the venture was uneconomic at the scale of its operations.<ref name=\":8\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.mrt.tas.gov.au/mrtdoc/dominfo/download/OS_204/OS_204.pdf|title=REPORT ON THE MINERAL RESOURCES OF THE BEACONSFIELD AND SALISBURY DISTRICTS.|last=Twelvetrees|first=W.H.|date=13 March 1903|website=|publisher=Government Geologist's Office, Launceston|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>\n\nPlans to raise capital and increase the scale of production lapsed, after the manager of the company\u2014Algernon Horatio Swifte\u2014died in early-1876. A quartz-reef rich in gold was discovered on land adjacent to the company's lease in mid-1877 and gold mining interests became interested in accessing the company's lease.  \n\nIn December 1877, the leases and other dormant assets of the THIC were sold cheaply to a group of wealthy and influential investors, under controversial circumstances. It soon became clear that the new owners\u2014collectively known at 'the Hematite Company'\u2014were interested in gold, not iron. In 1878, part of the THIC's original lease was combined with the operations of the adjacent 'Tasmania' gold mine, bringing huge profits to the new owners.  \n\n== Historical context ==\nSoon after the first settlement in Northern Tasmania, at [[York Town, Tasmania|York Town]] in 1804, colonial settlers found that there were extensive deposits of iron ore in the hills to the west of the Tamar estuary.<ref name=\":16\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.qvmag.tas.gov.au/files/assets/qvmag/library/.../tamar-valley-industrial.pdf|title=TAMAR VALLEY INDUSTRIAL HERITAGE \u2013 a survey|last=Morris-Nunn|first=Miranda|last2=Tassel|first2=C. B.|date=1984|website=|publisher=Queen Victoria Museum|pages=17|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> Interest in the area was aroused again by the report in 1866 of the Government Geologist, [[Charles Gould (geologist)|Charles Gould]].<ref name=\":17\">{{Cite news|url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article36638494|title=WEST TAMAR IRON FORMATION.|date=1866-09-28|work=Launceston Examiner (Tas. : 1842\u20131899)|access-date=2019-09-03|pages=2}}</ref>\n\nThere was an increase in pig-iron prices in the early 1870s, which led to the formation of a number of colonial-era iron-making ventures in Australia. The price of imported pig-iron increased, from \u00a34 10s per ton in 1870 to \u00a39 per ton in 1873 <ref name=\":21\">{{Cite book|title=Furnace, fire & forge : Lithgow's iron and steel industry, 1874\u20131932|last=McKillop, Robert F.|date=2006|publisher=Light Railway Research Society of Australia|others=Light Railway Research Society of Australia.|isbn=0-909340-44-7|location=Melbourne, Australia|pages=14|oclc=156757606}}</ref> greatly advantaging locally manufactured iron. However, this high price did not last long, as iron-making capacity increased and pig-iron was once again imported cheaply as ballast in sailing ships returning from England to Australia.\n\nThe Tamar Hematite Iron Company was one of four ventures that smelted iron from local iron ore, in Tasmania during the 1870s; the others were, the [[British and Tasmanian Charcoal Iron Company]], the [[Ilfracombe Iron Company]]\u2014both nearby on the Tamar estuary\u2014and the Derwent Iron Company. A fifth venture, the Swedish Charcoal Iron Company never went beyond issuing a prospectus. There were also three commercial iron-smelting operations in mainland Australia during the 1870s, the [[Fitzroy Iron Works#Fitzroy Bessemer Steel, Hematite, Iron and Coal Company (1873%E2%80%931883)|Fitzroy Iron Works]], the [[Lal Lal Iron Mine and Smelting Works#History of operations|Lal Lal Iron Company]], and the [[Lithgow Blast Furnace#History|Lithgow Valley Iron Works]].\n\nIn July 1877, the cap of a payable gold reef\u2014later known as the Tasmania Reef\u2014was discovered on the eastern slope of Cabbage Tree Hill by brothers William and David Dally,<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite news|url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article198918158|title=MINING NOTES.|date=1877-07-14|work=Tasmanian (Launceston, Tas. : 1871 - 1879)|access-date=2019-10-09|pages=9}}</ref> although alluvial gold was known to exist in the area for some years before then.\n\n== Iron ore deposit ==\nThe ore deposit was the sixth and last of the deposits in the West Tamar area that were mentioned by [[Charles Gould (geologist)|Charles Gould]] in his report of 1866.<ref name=\":163\" /> The area that the THIC would later mine lay on approximately 14-acres land to the east of Brandy Creek.<ref name=\":25\" /> Gould also noted that iron ore outcropped at various points in a line that \"''may be traced south-easterly continuously to Brandy Creek and thence in intervals along the flanks of Cabbage Tree Tier to the eastern side of Middle Arm Creek, some iron cropping out wherever the thickness of marine drift has been sufficiently stripped away to permit of its re-appearance''.\"<ref name=\":163\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.qvmag.tas.gov.au/files/assets/qvmag/library/.../tamar-valley-industrial.pdf|title=TAMAR VALLEY INDUSTRIAL HERITAGE \u2013 a survey|last=Morris-Nunn|first=Miranda|last2=Tassel|first2=C. B.|date=1984|website=|publisher=Queen Victoria Museum|pages=16, 22, 23|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>\n\nThe iron ore from the Brandy Creek mine was brown [[hematite]] or [[limonite]]\u2014wth recorded iron contents of 51.1% iron<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.mrt.tas.gov.au/mrtdoc/dominfo/download/OS_204/OS_204.pdf|title=REPORT ON THE MINERAL RESOURCES OF THE BEACONSFIELD AND SALISBURY DISTRICTS.|last=Twelvetrees|first=W.H.|date=13 March 1903|website=|publisher=Goverenment Geologist's Office, Launceston|page=36|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> and 46.8%<ref name=\":23\">{{Cite news|url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article187892382|title=IRON ORE DEPOSITS.|date=1919-06-02|work=World (Hobart, Tas. : 1918 - 1924)|access-date=2019-10-13|pages=3}}</ref>\u2014and was relatively rich compared to [[Cleveland Ironstone Formation|contemporary iron ore deposits in England]]. The THIC won a bronze medal for the iron ore that it exhibited at the [[Centennial Exposition|Centennial Exposition in Philidelphia]],<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article8941811|title=OUR LAUNCESTON LETTER.|date=1875-12-18|work=Mercury (Hobart, Tas. : 1860 - 1954)|access-date=2019-10-11|pages=2}}</ref> and first prize in its class for iron ore at the [[Victorian Intercolonial Exhibition|Victorian Intercolonial Exhibition of 1875]].<ref name=\":26\">{{Cite news|url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article52901492|title=AWARDS AT THE MELBOURNE EXHIBITION.|date=1875-09-21|work=Launceston Examiner (Tas. : 1842 - 1899)|access-date=2019-10-14|pages=2}}</ref>\n\n== History of operations ==\n\n=== Algernon Swifte and the foundation of the THIC ===\nThe company was formed around April 1873.<ref name=\":22\">{{Cite book|title=An iron will : mining at Beaconsfield - 1804 to 1877|last=Burch, Nigel|publisher=|year=|isbn=9780987371362|edition=   3rd|location=[Beaconsfield, Tasmania]|pages=193|oclc=1048604685}}</ref> The main proponent of the new company was a Tasmanian man, Algernon Horatio Swifte, who became its manager. \n\nHe enlisted a group of Melbourne-based investors, including Hastings Cuningham and John Benn,<ref>{{Cite book|title=An iron will : mining at Beaconsfield - 1804 to 1877|last=Burch, Nigel|publisher=|year=|isbn=9780987371362|edition=  3rd|location=[Beaconsfield, Tasmania]|pages=184\u2013189|oclc=1048604685}}</ref> both of whom were wealthy and influential men.<ref>{{Citation|last=Fearon|first=Frances|title=Cuningham, Hastings (1825\u20131908)|url=http://adb.anu.edu.au/biography/cuningham-hastings-276|work=Australian Dictionary of Biography|publisher=National Centre of Biography, Australian National University|access-date=2019-10-12}}</ref><ref>{{Citation|last=Hone|first=J. Ann|title=Benn, John (1821\u20131895)|url=http://adb.anu.edu.au/biography/benn-john-2973|work=Australian Dictionary of Biography|publisher=National Centre of Biography, Australian National University|access-date=2019-10-12}}</ref>\n\nIn June 1874, a new mineral lease over the THIC land was taken out in the personal names of Cuningham and Benn, presumably because they had contributed much of the capital for the new company.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article66071795|title=GOVERNMENT NOTICES AND APPOINTMENTS. I|date=1874-06-03|work=Cornwall Chronicle (Launceston, Tas. : 1835 - 1880)|access-date=2019-10-13|pages=3}}</ref>Only some 14-acres of the leased land\u2014east of Brandy Creek\u2014contained the future iron ore mine,<ref name=\":25\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.mrt.tas.gov.au/mrtdoc/dominfo/download/GSMR06/GSMR06.pdf|title=The Iron Ore Deposits of Tasmania|last=Twelvetrees and Reid|date=1919|website=|publisher=Tasmania Department of Mines|page=29|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> and much of the other leased land was probably intended to be a source of timber\u2014especially for charcoal burning\u2014although some of the land near Cabbage Tree Hill did contain more iron ore.<ref name=\":163\" /> However, all the leased land was leased under the The Mineral Leases Act, 1870, something that would later be of great significance. The THIC controlled 620-acres of leasehold land, and another 83-acres of freehold land\u2014in the area around what would become Swifte's Jetty\u2014just south from where Brandy Creek flowed into the Middle Arm of the Tamar estuary.<ref>{{Cite book|title=Brandy Creek : how Beaconsfield began|last=Burch, Nigel,|publisher=|isbn=9780987371317|edition=  First|location=[Beaconsfield, Tasmania]|pages=49|oclc=904742081|date = 15 April 2014}}</ref>\n\n=== Construction ===\nThe new company started work quickly. In November 1873, it was advertising for 100,000 bricks to be provided within four months of the order<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article8924364|title=Advertising|date=1873-11-12|work=Mercury (Hobart, Tas. : 1860 - 1954)|access-date=2019-10-13|pages=1}}</ref> and 20,000 feet of 4 inch by 4 inch hardwood timber in 12-foot or 15-foot lengths<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article52889765|title=Advertising|date=1873-11-18|work=Launceston Examiner (Tas. : 1842 - 1899)|access-date=2019-10-13|pages=6}}</ref>, which were the rails for its tramway. In early February 1874, Swifte returned from  Melbourne with 6000 fire bricks, fire clay and other material for the blast furnace lining.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article198925719|title=Miscellaneous.|date=1874-02-28|work=Tasmanian (Launceston, Tas. : 1871 - 1879)|access-date=2019-10-17|pages=11}}</ref> By March 1874, it was reported that \u201c''The Tamar Hematite Iron Company are progressing with their tramway and a small furnace, and hope to be successful in their experimental operations.''\u201d<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article66078385|title=OUR IRON MINES|date=1874-03-23|work=Cornwall Chronicle (Launceston, Tas. : 1835 - 1880)|access-date=2019-10-13|pages=3}}</ref>\n\nThe blast furnace was constructed on land, at a location now known as Scotchman\u2019s Point on the Middle Arm of the estuary of the Tamar River, close to the modern-day town of Beaconsfield.  It was constructed, on a rock shelf near the water's edge, against a rockface, so that the tramway could run on the level from the top of the rockface to the charging platform of the furnace. It has been described as a small experimental furnace.<ref name=\":22\" />\n\n=== Iron smelting operations ===\nA small test furnace\u2014made from sandstone quarried at the site\u2014was erected next to the blast furnace to test the ore. It made the first iron smelted from THIC iron ore on 5 December 1874. Using the little furnace \"''a quantity of pig iron was made, one piece weighing, about \u00bd[[cwt.]]'' [25kg], ''the slag ran well, separating. from the iron which ran freely''\" <ref name=\":13\">{{Cite news|url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article198923006|title=TAMAR HEMATITE IRON WORKS.|date=1874-12-12|work=Tasmanian (Launceston, Tas. : 1871 - 1879)|access-date=2019-10-09|pages=9}}</ref> This iron was worked by a blacksmith, Peter Massey, who pronounced it to be \"''excellent material to work, standing the filing well, and polishing more like steel than iron.''\"<ref name=\":13\" /><ref name=\":11\" />\n\nThe THIC's blast furnace was charged on New Year's Day 1875, and its first iron was tapped on 2 January 1875. This was the first production of pig-iron made from Tasmanian ore in a commercial quantity\u2014although others had made small quantities of iron earlier<ref name=\":12\" />\u2014and only the second commercial production of pig-iron from local ore in the six colonies that would later become Australia.<ref name=\":192\" /> The furnace worked well, being tapped every eight hours and casting pigs of 80 [[Pound (mass)|lbs]]. each that carried the brand, \"T.H.I. Co.- Charcoal.\"<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article52897046|title=TAMAR HEMATITE IRON COMPANY.|date=1875-01-07|work=Launceston Examiner (Tas. : 1842 - 1899)|access-date=2019-10-14|pages=2}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article66078026|title=THE TAMAR HEMATITE IRON COMPANY.|date=1875-01-06|work=Cornwall Chronicle (Launceston, Tas. : 1835 - 1880)|access-date=2019-10-14|pages=2}}</ref>\n\nIn late Jan 1875, the THIC was seeking tenders for shipping to Melbourne and seeking to employ charcoal burners.<ref name=\":27\">{{Cite news|url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article201487620|title=Advertising|date=1875-01-20|work=Tasmanian Tribune (Hobart Town, Tas. : 1872 - 1876)|access-date=2019-10-13|pages=1}}</ref> \n\n=== Suspension of operations and future plans ===\nBy the time that the THIC's smelting operations had begun, the price of iron in Australia had fallen from the peak of 1873.<ref name=\":21\" /> Despite the quality of its pig-iron, the company struggled to sell it in Melbourne, at prices that returned an adequate profit. The company's relatively small furnace did not make quantities large enough to sustain a viable operation at the lower prices.  \n\nSome iron was sent to Britain and 200 tons of it sold in Glasgow for \u00a36 7s 6d per ton, the landed cost in Britain being estimated as between \u00a34  and \u00a34 10s.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article151918164|title=TASMANIA'S IRON DEPOSITS|date=1908-07-23|work=Daily Telegraph (Launceston, Tas. : 1883 - 1928)|access-date=2020-01-28|pages=4}}</ref> In the long term, such an export market was not really viable, given the long distances involved. \n\nOperations were suspended in July 1875, after about 600 tons of pig-iron had been made.<ref name=\":8\" /> In August 1875, the THIC was asking that all accounts owing be submitted for payment. It seemed to be bringing the early operation to a financial as well as operational closure.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article72521468|title=Advertising|date=1875-08-09|work=Cornwall Chronicle (Launceston, Tas. : 1835 - 1880)|access-date=2019-10-14|pages=1}}</ref> At the beginning of September 1875, there was still some 200 tons of pig-iron at the works, which was gradually being shipped to market.<ref name=\":31\">{{Cite news|url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article52901230|title=MINING.|date=1875-09-04|work=Launceston Examiner (Tas. : 1842 - 1899)|access-date=2019-10-14|pages=3}}</ref> The THIC's pig-iron was being used at a local foundry in Launceston, in May 1876.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article233671123|title=A TRIP TO THE IRONWORKS|date=1876-05-27|work=Weekly Examiner (Launceston, Tas. : 1872 - 1878)|access-date=2019-10-14|pages=12}}</ref>\n\nAs early as January 1875, the THIC was tendering for up to 150,000 more bricks.<ref name=\":27\" /> It is likely that the bricks were intended for a larger furnace, which was never commenced. It seems that it had always planned to increase the smelting capacity of the works, and raise the additional capital to do so. As late as September 1875, the THIC's plan was reported to be \"''the re-organisation of the Company on a larger basis''\".<ref name=\":31\" />\n\n=== End of the Tamar Hematite Iron Company ===\nThe death of its manager Algernon Swift, in February 1876, was a major blow for the company. The THIC was facing a protracted period of low iron prices, during which its operations were suspended, without its dedicated Tasmanian manager and local representative. \n\nIn March 1877, the THIC's works at Swifte's Jetty were described as \"''deserted, desolate, and dull, suggestive of the much-lauded energy and enterprise of the Victorians in contradistinction to and at the expense of the Tasmanians !  Why those works should be allowed to go to \"wreck and ruin\" after so large an expenditure of capital, and with an inexhaustible supply of ore, remains a mystery to all but the initiated''.\"<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article198914805|title=SHARKING ON THE TAMAR.|date=1877-03-24|work=Tasmanian (Launceston, Tas. : 1871 - 1879)|access-date=2019-10-14|pages=5}}</ref> \n\nSuch unsympathetic views of the Victorian investors' plight turned more hostile, once payable quartz-reef gold was found in the area. Pressure to cancel the THIC's lease, supposedly to open it up for small-scale gold mining, was building.<ref name=\":0\" /><ref name=\":29\">{{Cite news|url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article198916311|title=Open Column.|date=1877-11-03|work=Tasmanian (Launceston, Tas. : 1871 - 1879)|access-date=2019-10-14|pages=6}}</ref> Some of those working to cancel the THIC's lease were Tasmanian politicians.<ref name=\":0\" />The THIC's view was that its holding the mineral lease for iron was not a barrier to gold mining, as it had consented to gold mining on its leasehold previously.<ref name=\":29\" />\n\nIn the face of increasing opposition\u2014and even parochial hostility\u2014to the THIC's mineral leases being held by [[Victoria (Australia)|Victorians]]<ref name=\":29\" />\u2014and with some perceived risk that those mineral leases might soon be cancelled, without compensation\u2014the THIC's Victorian shareholders finally gave up. In October 1877, the THIC resolved to dispose of its land and assets, with the stated hope that local Tasmanian capitalists might both resume the iron-making operation and work the gold.<ref name=\":29\" /> At the start of November 1877, the leases and assets were put up for sale.<ref name=\":30\" />  \n\nThe effective end of the THIC came on 10 December 1877, when the leases and other assets were sold to new owners.<ref name=\":19\" /> \n\n== Technology ==\n\n=== Process and equipment ===\n==== Blast furnace ====\nNo picture survives of the THIC blast furnace, but it was a small furnace that was similar in external appearance to the one at the Derwent Iron Company in Hobart.<ref name=\":9\">{{Cite news|url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article198922927|title=TAMAR HEMATITE IRON COMPANY.|date=1874-10-31|work=Tasmanian (Launceston, Tas. : 1871 - 1879)|access-date=2019-10-12|pages=6}}</ref><ref name=\":11\">{{Cite book|title=An iron will : mining at Beaconsfield - 1804 to 1877|last=Burch, Nigel|publisher=|year=|isbn=9780987371362|edition=  3rd|location=[Beaconsfield, Tasmania]|pages=193, 194, 195|oclc=1048604685}}</ref> The furnace was erected by Messrs Shields, of Hobart.<ref name=\":9\" />It was a \"Swedish\" cold-blast type, which used [[charcoal]] as its fuel and reducing agent. [[Limestone]] was used as a flux. \n\nThe furnace was designed to produce 20 to 25 tons of iron per week.<ref name=\":9\" /><ref name=\":11\" />It had the smallest capacity of the colonial-era blast furnaces that entered commercial production\u2014 a furnace of twelve times that capacity was used by the [[British and Tasmanian Charcoal Iron Company#Technology|British and Tasmanian Charcoal Iron Company]] and even the revived [[Fitzroy Iron Works]] furnace had five times the production capacity\u2014something that constrained the economic viability of the THIC operations, once iron prices fell from their peak of 1873. It seems that it was the company's intention\u2014having commenced operation and proven viability\u2014to seek more capital for a larger smelting operation.<ref name=\":31\" />\n\nThe blast furnace was constructed of [[Freestone (masonry)|freestone]]\u2014quarried on-site\u2014and bricks made from clay nearby, with a lining of imported English fire-bricks.<ref name=\":9\" /> <ref name=\":11\" />\"''The whole is substantially built, well bound together with strong hoops, arid the base firmly cramped, together.''\"<ref name=\":9\" /> It had three tuyeres, one on each side and one at the back.<ref name=\":9\" /><ref name=\":11\" />\n\nThe blast engine was a 16-horsepower (or 20-horsepower) horizontal-cylinder high-pressure (45-[[Pounds per square inch|psi]]) steam engine that powered two vertical blowing-cylinders\u2014of 30-inch diameter and 3-foot stroke\u2014via intermediate gearing from the shaft of the steam engine.<ref name=\":9\" /><ref name=\":11\" /> It was made by John Moore & Company, of Manchester<ref name=\":11\" /> and erected by Archibald and Jackson of Launceston.\n\n==== Charcoal kilns ====\nThere were two large charcoal kilns, each capable of turning out 1200 to 1500 [[Bushel|bushels]] of charcoal, over a period of three or four days and nights. <ref name=\":9\" />These were located alongside the tramway. There was a large charcoal storage shed near the blast furnace. <ref name=\":13\" />\n\nThe kilns were 10-feet wide by 50-feet long, and were constructed of slabs stuck on end into the ground. At one end the walls were 4-foot high, and gradually rose to 8-feet or 9-feet at the other end. Air-vents or \"nostril holes\" are formed in the sides 4-feet apart, by the insertion of earthen drain pipes. The inside walls were formed of sods, and then the kiln was filled with locally-cut wood, the top was covered with sods, and then fired. <ref name=\":9\" />\n\n=== Product quality ===\nThe pig-iron produced by the THIC's blast furnace was good quality and made good castings.<ref name=\":5\" /> THIC iron won first prize in its class at the [[Victorian Intercolonial Exhibition|Victorian Intercolonial Exhibition of 1875]].<ref name=\":26\" /><ref>{{Cite news|url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article72524632|title=THE INTERCOLONIAL EXHIBITION.|date=1875-09-20|work=Cornwall Chronicle (Launceston, Tas. : 1835 - 1880)|access-date=2019-10-14|pages=3}}</ref>\n\nAn analysis of the THIC pig-iron in England provided the results in the table below.<ref name=\":8\" />These results indicate a high quality pig-iron for its time, which\u2014except for the sulphur content\u2014would meet modern standards.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.metallics.org/pig-iron.html|title=Pig Iron|last=International Iron Metallics Association|date=2018-03-07|website=www.metallics.org|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2019-10-11}}</ref>\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|+THIC pig-iron analysis<ref name=\":8\" />\n|Iron\n|94.40%\n|-\n|Combined Carbon       \n|0.96%\n|-\n|Graphite (Carbon)\n|3.08%\n|-\n|Silicon\n|0.89%\n|-\n|Sulphur\n|0.22%\n|-\n|Phosphorus\n|0.09%\n|-\n|Manganese\n|0.24%\n|-\n|Loss\n|0.12%\n|-\n|'''Total'''\n|'''100.00%'''\n|}\n=== Transport ===\n\n==== Tramway ====\nThe tramway from the mine to Swifte's Jetty\u2014the site of the jetty, township and blast furnace\u2014was 1\u00be miles long. It ran through gently sloping country and required only three culverts to be constructed.<ref name=\":10\">{{Cite news|url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article52889765|title=Advertising|date=1873-11-18|work=Launceston Examiner (Tas. : 1842 - 1899)|access-date=2019-10-11|pages=6}}</ref><ref name=\":9\" /> At the blast furnace end, the tramway ran level right to the charging platform at the furnace top. There are two short branch tramways, one leading to the brick kiln and the other to the jetty.<ref name=\":13\" />\n\nThe tramway was horse-drawn. The gauge was 3-feet<ref name=\":9\" /> and the wooden rails were 4-inch by 4-inch hardwood timber.<ref name=\":10\" /><ref name=\":9\" /> Some of the wheels for the tramway trucks were cast from THIC pig-iron.<ref name=\":5\" />\n\n==== Jetty and shipping ====\nA timber jetty was erected on Middle Arm close to the site of the blast furnace. Materials and equipment was landed there during construction of other parts of the plant and the nearby township.\n\nThe water in the part of Middle Arm near the site of Swifte's Jetty is shallow and the bottom is exposed at low tide. [[Lighter (barge)|Lighters]] were used to carry the pig-iron to ships anchored in deeper water.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article8936524|title=THE MERCURY.|date=1875-04-13|work=Mercury (Hobart, Tas. : 1860 - 1954)|access-date=2019-10-13|pages=2}}</ref>Most of the iron was shipped to Melbourne, but some was shipped to England.\n\n== After iron ==\n\n=== Discovery of gold ===\nAfter iron mining on the THIC lease had ceased in mid-1875, the focus of mining interest around Brandy Creek\u2014now known as Beaconsfield\u2014became quartz-reef gold. The first of the significant quartz-reef gold mining companies, The Brandy Creek Quartz Gold Mining Company was established in December 1876. This company displaced some existing alluvial miners from its lease, and those miners moved to prospect in nearby areas.<ref>{{Cite book|title=An iron will : mining at Beaconsfield - 1804 to 1877|last=Burch, Nigel|publisher=|year=|isbn=9780987371362|edition=   3rd|location=[Beaconsfield, Tasmania]|pages=91|oclc=1048604685}}</ref>\n\nSome gold miners who held valid [[Miner's Right|Miner's Rights]] squatted on THIC lease\u2014with the expectation that the lease would be thrown open as a part of the surrounding goldfield<ref name=\":15\">{{Cite news|url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article233679936|title=Mining.|date=1878-03-16|work=Weekly Examiner (Launceston, Tas. : 1872 - 1878)|access-date=2019-10-12|pages=10}}</ref>\u2014and started to mine alluvial gold.<ref name=\":2\" />  Under the prevailing legislation, the THIC held the large lease only for the purpose of mining the iron ore and had no right to any gold found there, which  was legally the property of [[the Crown]].<ref name=\":3\" /> Some alluvial miners found payable amounts of gold on the THIC leasehold lands,<ref name=\":28\">{{Cite news|url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article233677155|title=GOLD NEWS|date=1877-09-15|work=Weekly Examiner (Launceston, Tas. : 1872 - 1878)|access-date=2019-10-14|pages=5}}</ref><ref name=\":7\" /> and some pegged claims.<ref name=\":28\" /><ref name=\":15\" />The dormant THIC did not interfere in any way with these small-scale gold mining operations; the company later claimed to have provided its consent to work gold on its lease to those whom had asked for it.<ref name=\":29\" />\n\nIn July 1877, the cap of a payable gold reef\u2014later known as the Tasmania Reef\u2014was discovered on the eastern slope of Cabbage Tree Hill, by brothers William and David Dally.<ref name=\":1\" /> Their claim was on [[Crown land#Australia|Crown land]], immediately adjacent to part of the THIC lease.\n\n=== Sale and new owners ===\nIt appears that at some point, the assets of the THIC were transferred to two of its major shareholders, Melbourne-based investors Hastings Cuningham and John Benn, in whose name the leaseholds were held. It was these two who subsequently put the assets and lease up for sale.<ref name=\":14\">{{Cite news|url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article233683493|title=THE HEMATITE IRON COMPANY.|date=1878-11-09|work=Weekly Examiner (Launceston, Tas. : 1872 - 1878)|access-date=2019-10-12|pages=20}}</ref> The assets and mineral lease of the THIC were originally advertised for a sale by auction on 22 November 1877,<ref name=\":30\">{{Cite news|url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article5943710|title=Advertising|date=1877-11-03|work=Argus (Melbourne, Vic. : 1848 - 1957)|access-date=2019-10-11|pages=10}}</ref> but the sale was deferred\u2014possibly twice<ref name=\":15\" />\u2014until 10 December 1877.<ref name=\":19\" />\n\nThe successful bidder was [[Adye Douglas|Ayde Douglas]]\u2014a prominent Tasmanian politician\u2014with a bid of just \u00a31,700.<ref name=\":19\">{{Cite news|url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article66068611|title=IRON.|date=1877-12-24|work=Cornwall Chronicle (Launceston, Tas. : 1835 - 1880)|access-date=2019-10-11|pages=6}}</ref> He was just one of the new owners. The others were three weathy Tasmanian politicians\u2014[[William Dawson Grubb]], [[William Hart (politician)|William Hart]], [[Members of the Tasmanian House of Assembly, 1872\u20131877|Samuel Tulloch]]\u2014and a Launceston merchant, John Murphy. All these other new owners had recently had dealings\u2014relevant to the THIC\u2014that were associated with gold mining; perhaps that was why it was Ayde Douglas\u2014an investor in the rival Ilfracombe Iron Company<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article52888782|title=OUR IRON MINES.|date=1873-09-20|work=Launceston Examiner (Tas. : 1842 - 1899)|access-date=2019-10-14|pages=5}}</ref> and later the buyer of its dormant assets<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article8929438|title=OUR LAUNCESTON LETTER.|date=1874-04-18|work=Mercury (Hobart, Tas. : 1860 - 1954)|access-date=2019-10-14|pages=3}}</ref>\u2014who bid for the THIC lands and assets.\n\nHart, Tulloch and Murphy had, as recently as October 1877, been attempting to have the THIC mineral lease cancelled but had failed.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite news|url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article37151635|title=GOLD NEWS.|date=1877-10-11|work=Launceston Examiner (Tas. : 1842 - 1899)|access-date=2019-10-10|pages=2}}</ref>\n\nGrubb and Hart had bought the Tasmania Reef claim from the Dally brothers, in October 1877, for \u00a35,000 and a tenth share of any company formed to mine the quartz reef.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article198916577|title=GOLD.|date=1877-10-13|work=Tasmanian (Launceston, Tas. : 1871 - 1879)|access-date=2019-10-10|pages=9}}</ref>The THIC leasehold adjoined the Tasmania Reef claim<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article895824|title=The Brisbane Courier.|date=1879-12-08|work=Brisbane Courier (Qld. : 1864 - 1933)|access-date=2019-10-11|pages=2}}</ref> but the full significance of that proximity was not apparent, at the time that Douglas acquired the THIC assets so cheaply.\n\nAlthough the sale of the lease and assets was the effective end of the Tamar Hematite Iron Company, the collective interest of new owners continued to be known as 'the Hematite Company' for some years later.<ref name=\":7\" /><ref name=\":14\" /> Their new property comprised \"''over 700 acres of freehold, leasehold, and other land, with buildings, machinery, and other property''\".<ref name=\":19\" />\n\n=== Mineral Lands Act of 1877 and dispute with gold miners ===\nOn 14 December 1877, Grubb and Hart visited the old THIC lease and gave the alluvial gold miners already working on the lease a notice to quit. This came about unexpectedly; the THIC mineral lease did not give the THIC right to mine gold and, previously,  the THIC had  consented to gold mining on its lease. It soon became known that the new owners' intransigent position was based on an interpretation of a newly-passed piece of legislation, the Mineral Lands Act of 1877.<ref name=\":2\">{{Cite news|url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article66068609|title=OUR GOLD MINES.|date=1877-12-24|work=Cornwall Chronicle (Launceston, Tas. : 1835 - 1880)|access-date=2019-10-10|pages=6}}</ref><ref name=\":3\">{{Cite news|url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article198917724|title=BRANDY CREEK GOLD FIELDS. WEST TAMAR.|date=1877-12-22|work=Tasmanian (Launceston, Tas. : 1871 - 1879)|access-date=2019-10-10|pages=4}}</ref><ref name=\":15\" />  \n\nThe Waste Lands Act 1863, first made provision for mineral leases for terms not exceeding twenty-one years, on any waste lands.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://eprints.utas.edu.au/22425/1/Whole-Meikle-thesis.pdf|title=Cronyism, Muddle and Money: Land Allocation in Tasmania under the Waste Lands Acts, 1856-1889|last=Meikle|first=Bronwyn|date=August 2014|website=|page=241|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> The THIC's lease for its leasehold land  was made under a later act, The Mineral Leases Act, 1870, which only gave the THIC a right to mine the iron ore, and not gold.<ref name=\":0\" /> Gold mining was subject to a separate Act, The Gold Fields Regulation Act, 1870.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://classic.austlii.edu.au/au/legis/tas/num_act/tgra187034vn6304/|title=The Goldfields Regulation Act, 1870 (34 Vic, No 6)|website=classic.austlii.edu.au|access-date=2019-10-10}}</ref> \n\nHowever, one day after the sale of the THIC lease and assets, the Mineral Lands Act of 1877, had come into force. Clause 30 of the new act effectively gave the holder of an existing mineral lease a [[Pre-emption right|pre-emptive right]] to take out a gold lease, if gold had been discovered on any part of the same land.<ref name=\":18\">{{Cite news|url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article233678570|title=THE MINERAL LANDS ACT|date=1877-12-22|work=Weekly Examiner (Launceston, Tas. : 1872 - 1878)|access-date=2019-10-12|pages=13}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.austlii.edu.au/cgi-bin/viewdoc/au/legis/tas/num_act/tmla187741vn7219/tmla187741vn7219.html|title=Mineral Lands Act, 1877|last=Tasmanian Parliamant|date=11 December 1877|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>It seems it was an unintended consequence of a clause intended to prevent alluvial tin miners failing to recover gold that was present on their tin-mining leases and to prevent such gold going to waste. However, it is possible that the tin-mining case was only a rationalisation, to justify a [[loophole]] that had been created\u2014perhaps deliberately\u2014in the legislation. \n\nAfter buying the mineral lease, the new owners immediately paid the arrears rent for the lease (\u00a3310) and then\u2014as a lessee in good standing until 31 December 1877\u2014pegged a gold mining claim,<ref name=\":15\" />under The Gold Fields Regulation Act. According to the Goldfield Regulation Act, a gold mining claim needed to be on public display for a period of 30-days, but the new owners had back-dated their claim, allowing no time for an objection to be raised.<ref name=\":162\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.qvmag.tas.gov.au/files/assets/qvmag/library/.../tamar-valley-industrial.pdf|title=TAMAR VALLEY INDUSTRIAL HERITAGE \u2013 a survey|last=Morris-Nunn|first=Miranda|last2=Tassel|first2=C. B.|date=1984|website=|publisher=Queen Victoria Museum|pages=63|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>  \n\nOvernight, the price paid for the leased land and other THIC assets by the new owners\u2014mainly wealthy Tasmanian politicians\u2014became a remarkable bargain. The buyers' cronyism, connivance, and conflict of interest\u2014as politicians who had recently debated and voted upon the new Act\u2014seemed obvious,<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article198917724|title=BRANDY CREEK GOLD FIELDS. WEST TAMAR.|date=1877-12-22|work=Tasmanian (Launceston, Tas. : 1871 - 1879)|access-date=2019-10-11|pages=4}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article201724526|title=No title|date=1879-03-27|work=Tribune (Hobart, Tas. : 1876 - 1879)|access-date=2019-10-10|pages=2}}</ref> but their actions had been completely legal.<ref>{{Cite book|title=An iron will : mining at Beaconsfield - 1804 to 1877|last=Burch, Nigel|publisher=|year=|isbn=9780987371362|edition=   3rd|location=[Beaconsfield, Tasmania]|pages=240\u2013243|oclc=1048604685}}</ref> \n\nThe new arrangements were controversial<ref name=\":18\" />; there was disputation, during 1878 and 1879, between the new owners\u2014collectively known as 'the Hematite Company'\u2014and the small-scale gold miners,<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article66504118|title=MINING NOTES.|date=1879-03-07|work=Cornwall Chronicle (Launceston, Tas. : 1835 - 1880)|access-date=2019-10-12|pages=2}}</ref> and protests from others concerned about the probity of the way the new owners had acquired the gold rights.<ref name=\":15\" /><ref name=\":14\" /><ref name=\":18\" /> \n\n=== Quartz reef mining on the 'Hematite Company' lease ===\nBy October 1878, it had become well known that the rich Tasmania Reef extended onto the old THIC  leasehold land. A new company, The Tasmania Extended Gold Mining Company was set up to mine gold, on ten acres of land on Cabbage Tree Hill, due east of the Tasmanian Mine lease and to the south of two other gold leases. The land included a part of the bounteous Tasmania Reef, which could be accessed by extending the workings of the Tasmania Mine over the boundary of the 'Hematite Company' lease. The 'Hematite Company' interests received a small number of shares in the new company, but received a lucrative 5% royalty on the gold mined.<ref name=\":7\">{{Cite news|url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article66501753|title=Advertising|date=1878-10-29|work=Cornwall Chronicle (Launceston, Tas. : 1835 - 1880)|access-date=2019-10-11|pages=3}}</ref><ref name=\":14\" />\n\nThe Tasmania Mine had paid dividends of over \u00a3700,000 by 1900.<ref name=\"Saclier\">M. J. Saclier: [http://adb.anu.edu.au/biography/grubb-william-dawson-3676/text5743 ''Grubb, William Dawson (1817\u20131879)''], Australian Dictionary of Biography, National Centre of Biography, Australian National University, published first in hardcopy 1972, accessed online 16 January 2018.</ref>It was one of the deepest and richest mines in Australia, by the time it closed in 1914.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.beaconsfieldgold.com.au/CompanyProfile.html|title=History of Gold at Beaconsfield|work=Company Profile|publisher=Beaconsfield Gold NL|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://archive.is/20060511233844/http://www.beaconsfieldgold.com.au/CompanyProfile.html|archivedate=11 May 2006|accessdate=2006-05-09}}</ref>Although William Grubb died in 1879, his family\u2014benefiting from both his share of the Tasmania Mine and the 'Hematite Company' royalty\u2014became  even more weathly<ref name=\"Saclier\" /><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.australiancountry.com.au/updates/a-proud-family-home/|title=A PROUD FAMILY HOME|date=2016-12-12|website=Australian Country|language=en|access-date=2019-10-11}}</ref>, as did the other partners in 'the Hematite Company'.\n\n=== Iron ore deposit ===\nAlthough the underground quartz reef workings would not affect the surface quarrying of iron ore, the surface workings were also soon thrown open to gold mining. The 'Hematite Company' agreed, in March 1879, to allow alluvial miners to work parts of the old lease.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article201726673|title=No title|date=1879-03-28|work=Tribune (Hobart, Tas. : 1876 - 1879)|access-date=2019-10-12|pages=2}}</ref> ; their decision to accept this compromise outcome foreshadowed an amendment made, in November 1880, to the legislation.<ref name=\":20\">{{Cite news|url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article38264661|title=LAUNCESTON EXAMINER.|date=1880-11-20|work=Launceston Examiner (Tas. : 1842 - 1899)|access-date=2019-10-12|pages=2}}</ref>\n\nThe THIC lease's iron ore was not used again,<ref name=\":6\" />apart from during 1890\u20131892, when 1,000 tons of ore were shipped to Melbourne for [[History of manufactured fuel gases#Appliances and machinery of the historic gas-works|town gas purification]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.mrt.tas.gov.au/mrtdoc/dominfo/download/OS_204/OS_204.pdf|title=REPORT ON THE MINERAL RESOURCES OF THE BEACONSFIELD AND SALISURY DISTRICTS|last=Twelvetrees|first=W.H.|date=13 March 1903|website=|publisher=Government Geologist's Office, Launceston|page=6, 7|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref><ref name=\":23\" />\n\n=== Other ex-THIC assets ===\nSwifte's Jetty was replaced in 1879<ref name=\":24\" /> and the replacement jetty was used to land gold mining equipment,<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article38262613|title=MINING INTELLIGENCE.|last=|first=|date=1880-09-16|work=Launceston Examiner (Tas. : 1842 - 1899)|access-date=2019-10-11|pages=2}}</ref> Presumably, the tramway that conveniently ran east-west from the jetty to near the gold mines stayed in use for a while too. \n\nThe blast furnace was still standing in 1883, when the government geologist, Gustav Thureau, collected samples of THIC iron from its hearth.<ref name=\":210\">{{Cite book|title=An iron will : mining at Beaconsfield - 1804 to 1877|last=Burch, Nigel|publisher=|year=|isbn=9780987371362|edition= 3rd|location=[Beaconsfield, Tasmania]|pages=181, 182|oclc=1048604685}}</ref> Its blast engine and blowing cylinders were still there in November 1883; this is known because Alfred Ritchie was later charged with stealing two engine cylinders to sell as scrap iron. The cylinders had been broken up, before being sold to a foundry in Launceston.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article199529545|title=GEORGE TOWN POLICE COURT|date=1884-06-14|work=Tasmanian (Launceston, Tas. : 1881 - 1895)|access-date=2019-10-12|pages=22}}</ref> \n\n== Legacy and remnants ==\nThe Mineral Lands Act of 1877 was amended in November 1880. The new act repealed Clause 30 of the 1877 Act,<ref name=\":20\" /><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://classic.austlii.edu.au/au/legis/tas/num_act/tmlaa188044vn17299/tmlaa188044vn17299.pdf|title=An Act to amend the Mineral Lands Act of 1877|last=Tasmanian Government|date=1 November 1880|website=1877 Tasmanian Numbered Acts - AustLII|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> under which the buyers of the THIC assets had craftily acquired a fortune in gold, at the small cost of \u00a31,700 and \u00a3310 in arrears rent.\n\nThe jetty and the township at Swifte's Jetty on the Middle Arm of the Tamar River estuary\u2014at the locality now known as Scotchman's Point\u2014are now long gone. Any remains of the blast furnace were buried under gold mine tailings that were reprocessed during the 1980s.<ref name=\":4\">{{Cite book|title=An iron will : mining at Beaconsfield - 1804 to 1877|last=Burch, Nigel|publisher=|year=|isbn=9780987371362|edition=   3rd|location=[Beaconsfield, Tasmania]|pages=243|oclc=1048604685}}</ref> The area where the old town and iron plant stood was still known as \"Swift's ''[sic]'' Jetty\"  well into the 20th-Century,<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article91417141|title=BEACONSFIELD COUNCIL|date=1944-10-17|work=Examiner (Launceston, Tas. : 1900 - 1954)|access-date=2019-10-12|pages=3}}</ref> but is no longer known by that name. Algernon Swifte himself is largely forgotten.<ref name=\":24\">{{Cite book|title=An iron will : mining at Beaconsfield - 1804 to 1877|last=Burch, Nigel|publisher=|year=|isbn=9780987371362|edition=  3rd|location=[Beaconsfield, Tasmania]|pages=243|oclc=1048604685}}</ref> \n\nThe site of the THIC iron ore mine, near Brandy Creek slightly north-west of the modern-day town of Beaconsfield, is now reserved as a source of gravel; iron ore still outcrops at the site.<ref name=\":6\">{{Cite book|title=An iron will : mining at Beaconsfield - 1804 to 1877|last=Burch, Nigel|publisher=|year=|isbn=9780987371362|edition=  3rd|location=[Beaconsfield, Tasmania]|pages=196|oclc=1048604685}}</ref>Although it still contains iron ore, the ore deposit is far too small and not rich enough to be commercially viable today. \n\nA part of the cast iron fence of the Pilgrim [[Uniting Church in Australia|Uniting Church]]\u2014built as a [[Wesleyan theology|Wesleyan]] Church\u2014in Paterson St, Launceston is made from pig-iron made by the THIC. The fencing was among the castings made at the foundry of William Peters, in Wellington St, Launceston, in late April 1875.<ref>{{Cite book|title=An iron will : mining at Beaconsfield - 1804 to 1877|last=Burch, Nigel|publisher=|year=|isbn=9780987371362|edition=   3rd|location=[Beaconsfield, Tasmania]|pages=204, 205|oclc=1048604685}}</ref><ref name=\":5\">{{Cite news|url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article8936968|title=OUR LAUNCESTON LETTER.|date=1875-05-01|work=Mercury (Hobart, Tas. : 1860 - 1954)|access-date=2019-10-10|pages=2}}</ref>\n\n== See also ==\n\n* [[British and Tasmanian Charcoal Iron Company]] \n* [[Ilfracombe Iron Company]]\n* [[Beaconsfield, Tasmania]]\n\n== References ==\n<!--- See [[Wikipedia:Footnotes]] on how to create references using <ref></ref> tags which will then appear here automatically -->\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n<!-- Use the format: * [http://www.example.com/ example.com] -->\n\n<!--- Categories --->*[http://classic.austlii.edu.au/au/legis/tas/num_act/tmla187034vn11229/ <nowiki>Mineral Leases Act of 1870 [18 October, 1870]</nowiki>]\n*[http://www.austlii.edu.au/cgi-bin/viewdoc/au/legis/tas/num_act/tmla187741vn7219/tmla187741vn7219.html <nowiki>The Mineral Lands Act of 1877 [11 December 1877]</nowiki>]\n*[http://classic.austlii.edu.au/au/legis/tas/num_act/tmlaa188044vn17299/tmlaa188044vn17299.pdf <nowiki>An Act to amend \"The Mineral Lands Act of 1877\" [1 November 1880]</nowiki>]\n*[http://www.mrt.tas.gov.au/mrtdoc/dominfo/download/OS_204/OS_204.pdf \"Report on the Mineral Resources of the Districts of Beaconsfield and Salisbury\", W.H.Twelvetrees, Government Geologist's Office, Launceston 13 March 1903]\n*[http://www.mrt.tas.gov.au/mrtdoc/dominfo/download/GSMR06/GSMR06.pdf \"The Iron Ore Deposits of Tasmania\", W.H.Twelvetrees and A.M.Reid, Tasmania Department of Mines (1919)]\n\n<br />\n\n{{coord missing|Tasmania}}\n\n[[Category:Iron mining in Australia]]\n[[Category:Mines in Tasmania]]\n[[Category:1874 establishments in Australia]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date = March 2012}}\n\n{{Use Australian English|date = March 2012}}\n\nThe '''Tamar Hematite Iron Company''' (THIC) was an iron mining and smelting company that operated from April 1874 to December 1877, in the area close to the location of the modern-day township of [[Beaconsfield, Tasmania|Beaconsfield]],[[Tasmania]], Australia.\n\nThe company's operations consisted of an iron ore mine near Brandy Creek, a blast furnace, jetty and township, on the Middle Arm of the estuary of the [[Kanamaluka / Tamar River|Tamar River]], a tramway connecting the two sites, and charcoal and brick kilns. \n\nThe THIC was the first company to produce iron in commercial quantities from Tasmanian ore and bring their product to market, although others had made small quantities earlier.<ref name=\":12\">{{Cite news|url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article66072629|title=TAMAR HEMATITE IRON COMPANY|last=|first=|date=1875-01-04|work=Cornwall Chronicle (Launceston, Tas. : 1835 - 1880)|access-date=2019-10-09|pages=2}}</ref> It was the second company in Australia\u2014at the time considered to be six separate self-governing British colonies\u2014to make commercial quantities of pig-iron that was smelted from Australian iron ore.<ref name=\":192\">{{Cite book|title=Furnace, fire & forge : Lithgow's iron and steel industry, 1874\u20131932|last=McKillop, Robert F.|date=2006|publisher=Light Railway Research Society of Australia|others=Light Railway Research Society of Australia.|isbn=0909340447|location=Melbourne, Australia|pages=16, 17|oclc=156757606}}</ref><ref name=\":110\">{{Cite book|title=The Lal Lal Blast Furnace Reserve report|last=Staughton|first=Peter Samuel|date=1976|publisher=[National Trust of Australia, Victoria]|others=Ashley, Robert William P.,, National Trust of Australia (Vic.), Lal Lal Blast Furnace Reserve. Committee of Management.|isbn=090971018X|location=[South Yarra, Vic.]|pages=124|oclc=27604498}}</ref>\n\n[[Pig iron|Pig-iron]] of good quality was made in its blast furnace from January 1875, until July 1875 when operations were suspended. Complicated by a decline in the price of pig iron, the venture was uneconomic at the scale of its operations.<ref name=\":8\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.mrt.tas.gov.au/mrtdoc/dominfo/download/OS_204/OS_204.pdf|title=REPORT ON THE MINERAL RESOURCES OF THE BEACONSFIELD AND SALISBURY DISTRICTS.|last=Twelvetrees|first=W.H.|date=13 March 1903|website=|publisher=Government Geologist's Office, Launceston|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>\n\nPlans to raise capital and increase the scale of production lapsed, after the manager of the company\u2014Algernon Horatio Swifte\u2014died in early-1876. A quartz-reef rich in gold was discovered on land adjacent to the company's lease in mid-1877 and gold mining interests became interested in accessing the company's lease.  \n\nIn December 1877, the leases and other dormant assets of the THIC were sold cheaply to a group of wealthy and influential investors, under controversial circumstances. It soon became clear that the new owners\u2014collectively known at 'the Hematite Company'\u2014were interested in gold, not iron. In 1878, part of the THIC's original lease was combined with the operations of the adjacent 'Tasmania' gold mine, bringing huge profits to the new owners.  \n\n== Historical context ==\nSoon after the first settlement in Northern Tasmania, at [[York Town, Tasmania|York Town]] in 1804, colonial settlers found that there were extensive deposits of iron ore in the hills to the west of the Tamar estuary.<ref name=\":16\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.qvmag.tas.gov.au/files/assets/qvmag/library/.../tamar-valley-industrial.pdf|title=TAMAR VALLEY INDUSTRIAL HERITAGE \u2013 a survey|last=Morris-Nunn|first=Miranda|last2=Tassel|first2=C. B.|date=1984|website=|publisher=Queen Victoria Museum|pages=17|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> Interest in the area was aroused again by the report in 1866 of the Government Geologist, [[Charles Gould (geologist)|Charles Gould]].<ref name=\":17\">{{Cite news|url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article36638494|title=WEST TAMAR IRON FORMATION.|date=1866-09-28|work=Launceston Examiner (Tas. : 1842\u20131899)|access-date=2019-09-03|pages=2}}</ref>\n\nThere was an increase in pig-iron prices in the early 1870s, which led to the formation of a number of colonial era iron-making ventures in Australia. The price of imported pig-iron increased, from \u00a34 10s per ton in 1870 to \u00a39 per ton in 1873 <ref name=\":21\">{{Cite book|title=Furnace, fire & forge : Lithgow's iron and steel industry, 1874\u20131932|last=McKillop, Robert F.|date=2006|publisher=Light Railway Research Society of Australia|others=Light Railway Research Society of Australia.|isbn=0-909340-44-7|location=Melbourne, Australia|pages=14|oclc=156757606}}</ref> greatly advantaging locally manufactured iron. However, this high price did not last long, as iron-making capacity increased and pig-iron was once again imported cheaply as ballast in sailing ships returning from England to Australia.\n\nThe Tamar Hematite Iron Company was one of four ventures that smelted iron from local iron ore, in Tasmania during the 1870s; the others were, the [[British and Tasmanian Charcoal Iron Company]], the [[Ilfracombe Iron Company]]\u2014both nearby on the Tamar estuary\u2014and the Derwent Iron Company. A fifth venture, the Swedish Charcoal Iron Company never went beyond issuing a prospectus. There were also three commercial iron-smelting operations in mainland Australia during the 1870s, the [[Fitzroy Iron Works#Fitzroy Bessemer Steel, Hematite, Iron and Coal Company (1873%E2%80%931883)|Fitzroy Iron Works]], the [[Lal Lal Iron Mine and Smelting Works#History of operations|Lal Lal Iron Company]], and the [[Lithgow Blast Furnace#History|Lithgow Valley Iron Works]].\n\nIn July 1877, the cap of a payable gold reef\u2014later known as the Tasmania Reef\u2014was discovered on the eastern slope of Cabbage Tree Hill by brothers William and David Dally,<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite news|url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article198918158|title=MINING NOTES.|date=1877-07-14|work=Tasmanian (Launceston, Tas. : 1871 - 1879)|access-date=2019-10-09|pages=9}}</ref> although alluvial gold was known to exist in the area for some years before then.\n\n== Iron ore deposit ==\nThe ore deposit was the sixth and last of the deposits in the West Tamar area that were mentioned by [[Charles Gould (geologist)|Charles Gould]] in his report of 1866.<ref name=\":163\" /> The area that the THIC would later mine lay on approximately 14-acres land to the east of Brandy Creek.<ref name=\":25\" /> Gould also noted that iron ore outcropped at various points in a line that \"''may be traced south-easterly continuously to Brandy Creek and thence in intervals along the flanks of Cabbage Tree Tier to the eastern side of Middle Arm Creek, some iron cropping out wherever the thickness of marine drift has been sufficiently stripped away to permit of its re-appearance''.\"<ref name=\":163\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.qvmag.tas.gov.au/files/assets/qvmag/library/.../tamar-valley-industrial.pdf|title=TAMAR VALLEY INDUSTRIAL HERITAGE \u2013 a survey|last=Morris-Nunn|first=Miranda|last2=Tassel|first2=C. B.|date=1984|website=|publisher=Queen Victoria Museum|pages=16, 22, 23|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>\n\nThe iron ore from the Brandy Creek mine was brown [[hematite]] or [[limonite]]\u2014wth recorded iron contents of 51.1% iron<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.mrt.tas.gov.au/mrtdoc/dominfo/download/OS_204/OS_204.pdf|title=REPORT ON THE MINERAL RESOURCES OF THE BEACONSFIELD AND SALISBURY DISTRICTS.|last=Twelvetrees|first=W.H.|date=13 March 1903|website=|publisher=Goverenment Geologist's Office, Launceston|page=36|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> and 46.8%<ref name=\":23\">{{Cite news|url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article187892382|title=IRON ORE DEPOSITS.|date=1919-06-02|work=World (Hobart, Tas. : 1918 - 1924)|access-date=2019-10-13|pages=3}}</ref>\u2014and was relatively rich compared to [[Cleveland Ironstone Formation|contemporary iron ore deposits in England]]. The THIC won a bronze medal for the iron ore that it exhibited at the [[Centennial Exposition|Centennial Exposition in Philidelphia]],<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article8941811|title=OUR LAUNCESTON LETTER.|date=1875-12-18|work=Mercury (Hobart, Tas. : 1860 - 1954)|access-date=2019-10-11|pages=2}}</ref> and first prize in its class for iron ore at the [[Victorian Intercolonial Exhibition|Victorian Intercolonial Exhibition of 1875]].<ref name=\":26\">{{Cite news|url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article52901492|title=AWARDS AT THE MELBOURNE EXHIBITION.|date=1875-09-21|work=Launceston Examiner (Tas. : 1842 - 1899)|access-date=2019-10-14|pages=2}}</ref>\n\n== History of operations ==\n\n=== Algernon Swifte and the foundation of the THIC ===\nThe company was formed around April 1873.<ref name=\":22\">{{Cite book|title=An iron will : mining at Beaconsfield - 1804 to 1877|last=Burch, Nigel|publisher=|year=|isbn=9780987371362|edition=   3rd|location=[Beaconsfield, Tasmania]|pages=193|oclc=1048604685}}</ref> The main proponent of the new company was a Tasmanian man, Algernon Horatio Swifte, who became its manager. \n\nHe enlisted a group of Melbourne-based investors, including Hastings Cuningham and John Benn,<ref>{{Cite book|title=An iron will : mining at Beaconsfield - 1804 to 1877|last=Burch, Nigel|publisher=|year=|isbn=9780987371362|edition=  3rd|location=[Beaconsfield, Tasmania]|pages=184\u2013189|oclc=1048604685}}</ref> both of whom were wealthy and influential men.<ref>{{Citation|last=Fearon|first=Frances|title=Cuningham, Hastings (1825\u20131908)|url=http://adb.anu.edu.au/biography/cuningham-hastings-276|work=Australian Dictionary of Biography|publisher=National Centre of Biography, Australian National University|access-date=2019-10-12}}</ref><ref>{{Citation|last=Hone|first=J. Ann|title=Benn, John (1821\u20131895)|url=http://adb.anu.edu.au/biography/benn-john-2973|work=Australian Dictionary of Biography|publisher=National Centre of Biography, Australian National University|access-date=2019-10-12}}</ref>\n\nIn June 1874, a new mineral lease over the THIC land was taken out in the personal names of Cuningham and Benn, presumably because they had contributed much of the capital for the new company.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article66071795|title=GOVERNMENT NOTICES AND APPOINTMENTS. I|date=1874-06-03|work=Cornwall Chronicle (Launceston, Tas. : 1835 - 1880)|access-date=2019-10-13|pages=3}}</ref>Only some 14-acres of the leased land\u2014east of Brandy Creek\u2014contained the future iron ore mine,<ref name=\":25\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.mrt.tas.gov.au/mrtdoc/dominfo/download/GSMR06/GSMR06.pdf|title=The Iron Ore Deposits of Tasmania|last=Twelvetrees and Reid|date=1919|website=|publisher=Tasmania Department of Mines|page=29|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> and much of the other leased land was probably intended to be a source of timber\u2014especially for charcoal burning\u2014although some of the land near Cabbage Tree Hill did contain more iron ore.<ref name=\":163\" /> However, all the leased land was leased under the The Mineral Leases Act, 1870, something that would later be of great significance. The THIC controlled 620-acres of leasehold land, and another 83-acres of freehold land\u2014in the area around what would become Swifte's Jetty\u2014just south from where Brandy Creek flowed into the Middle Arm of the Tamar estuary.<ref>{{Cite book|title=Brandy Creek : how Beaconsfield began|last=Burch, Nigel,|publisher=|isbn=9780987371317|edition=  First|location=[Beaconsfield, Tasmania]|pages=49|oclc=904742081|date = 15 April 2014}}</ref>\n\n=== Construction ===\nThe new company started work quickly. In November 1873, it was advertising for 100,000 bricks to be provided within four months of the order<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article8924364|title=Advertising|date=1873-11-12|work=Mercury (Hobart, Tas. : 1860 - 1954)|access-date=2019-10-13|pages=1}}</ref> and 20,000 feet of 4 inch by 4 inch hardwood timber in 12-foot or 15-foot lengths<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article52889765|title=Advertising|date=1873-11-18|work=Launceston Examiner (Tas. : 1842 - 1899)|access-date=2019-10-13|pages=6}}</ref>, which were the rails for its tramway. In early February 1874, Swifte returned from  Melbourne with 6000 fire bricks, fire clay and other material for the blast furnace lining.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article198925719|title=Miscellaneous.|date=1874-02-28|work=Tasmanian (Launceston, Tas. : 1871 - 1879)|access-date=2019-10-17|pages=11}}</ref> By March 1874, it was reported that \u201c''The Tamar Hematite Iron Company are progressing with their tramway and a small furnace, and hope to be successful in their experimental operations.''\u201d<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article66078385|title=OUR IRON MINES|date=1874-03-23|work=Cornwall Chronicle (Launceston, Tas. : 1835 - 1880)|access-date=2019-10-13|pages=3}}</ref>\n\nThe blast furnace was constructed on land, at a location now known as Scotchman\u2019s Point on the Middle Arm of the estuary of the Tamar River, close to the modern-day town of Beaconsfield.  It was constructed, on a rock shelf near the water's edge, against a rockface, so that the tramway could run on the level from the top of the rockface to the charging platform of the furnace. It has been described as a small experimental furnace.<ref name=\":22\" />\n\n=== Iron smelting operations ===\nA small test furnace\u2014made from sandstone quarried at the site\u2014was erected next to the blast furnace to test the ore. It made the first iron smelted from THIC iron ore on 5 December 1874. Using the little furnace \"''a quantity of pig iron was made, one piece weighing, about \u00bd[[cwt.]]'' [25kg], ''the slag ran well, separating. from the iron which ran freely''\" <ref name=\":13\">{{Cite news|url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article198923006|title=TAMAR HEMATITE IRON WORKS.|date=1874-12-12|work=Tasmanian (Launceston, Tas. : 1871 - 1879)|access-date=2019-10-09|pages=9}}</ref> This iron was worked by a blacksmith, Peter Massey, who pronounced it to be \"''excellent material to work, standing the filing well, and polishing more like steel than iron.''\"<ref name=\":13\" /><ref name=\":11\" />\n\nThe THIC's blast furnace was charged on New Year's Day 1875, and its first iron was tapped on 2 January 1875. This was the first production of pig-iron made from Tasmanian ore in a commercial quantity\u2014although others had made small quantities of iron earlier<ref name=\":12\" />\u2014and only the second commercial production of pig-iron from local ore in the six colonies that would later become Australia.<ref name=\":192\" /> The furnace worked well, being tapped every eight hours and casting pigs of 80 [[Pound (mass)|lbs]]. each that carried the brand, \"T.H.I. Co.- Charcoal.\"<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article52897046|title=TAMAR HEMATITE IRON COMPANY.|date=1875-01-07|work=Launceston Examiner (Tas. : 1842 - 1899)|access-date=2019-10-14|pages=2}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article66078026|title=THE TAMAR HEMATITE IRON COMPANY.|date=1875-01-06|work=Cornwall Chronicle (Launceston, Tas. : 1835 - 1880)|access-date=2019-10-14|pages=2}}</ref>\n\nIn late Jan 1875, the THIC was seeking tenders for shipping to Melbourne and seeking to employ charcoal burners.<ref name=\":27\">{{Cite news|url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article201487620|title=Advertising|date=1875-01-20|work=Tasmanian Tribune (Hobart Town, Tas. : 1872 - 1876)|access-date=2019-10-13|pages=1}}</ref> \n\n=== Suspension of operations and future plans ===\nBy the time that the THIC's smelting operations had begun, the price of iron in Australia had fallen from the peak of 1873.<ref name=\":21\" /> Despite the quality of its pig-iron, the company struggled to sell it in Melbourne, at prices that returned an adequate profit. The company's relatively small furnace did not make quantities large enough to sustain a viable operation at the lower prices.  \n\nSome iron was sent to Britain and 200 tons of it sold in Glasgow for \u00a36 7s 6d per ton, the landed cost in Britain being estimated as between \u00a34  and \u00a34 10s.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article151918164|title=TASMANIA'S IRON DEPOSITS|date=1908-07-23|work=Daily Telegraph (Launceston, Tas. : 1883 - 1928)|access-date=2020-01-28|pages=4}}</ref> In the long term, such an export market was not really viable, given the long distances involved. \n\nOperations were suspended in July 1875, after about 600 tons of pig-iron had been made.<ref name=\":8\" /> In August 1875, the THIC was asking that all accounts owing be submitted for payment. It seemed to be bringing the early operation to a financial as well as operational closure.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article72521468|title=Advertising|date=1875-08-09|work=Cornwall Chronicle (Launceston, Tas. : 1835 - 1880)|access-date=2019-10-14|pages=1}}</ref> At the beginning of September 1875, there was still some 200 tons of pig-iron at the works, which was gradually being shipped to market.<ref name=\":31\">{{Cite news|url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article52901230|title=MINING.|date=1875-09-04|work=Launceston Examiner (Tas. : 1842 - 1899)|access-date=2019-10-14|pages=3}}</ref> The THIC's pig-iron was being used at a local foundry in Launceston, in May 1876.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article233671123|title=A TRIP TO THE IRONWORKS|date=1876-05-27|work=Weekly Examiner (Launceston, Tas. : 1872 - 1878)|access-date=2019-10-14|pages=12}}</ref>\n\nAs early as Jan 1875, the THIC was tendering for up to 150,000 more bricks.<ref name=\":27\" /> It is likely that the bricks were intended for a larger furnace, which was never commenced. It seems that it had always planned to increase the smelting capacity of the works, and raise the additional capital to do so. As late as September 1875, the THIC's plan was reported to be \"''the re-organisation of the Company on a larger basis''\".<ref name=\":31\" />\n\n=== End of the Tamar Hematite Iron Company ===\nThe death of its manager Algernon Swift, in February 1876, was a major blow for the company. The THIC was facing a protracted period of low iron prices, during which its operations were suspended, without its dedicated Tasmanian manager and local representative. \n\nIn March 1877, the THIC's works at Swifte's Jetty were described as \"''deserted, desolate, and dull, suggestive of the much-lauded energy and enterprise of the Victorians in contradistinction to and at the expense of the Tasmanians !  Why those works should be allowed to go to \"wreck and ruin\" after so large an expenditure of capital, and with an inexhaustible supply of ore, remains a mystery to all but the initiated''.\"<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article198914805|title=SHARKING ON THE TAMAR.|date=1877-03-24|work=Tasmanian (Launceston, Tas. : 1871 - 1879)|access-date=2019-10-14|pages=5}}</ref> \n\nSuch unsympathetic views of the Victorian investors' plight turned more hostile, once payable quartz-reef gold was found in the area. Pressure to cancel the THIC's lease, supposedly to open it up for small-scale gold mining, was building.<ref name=\":0\" /><ref name=\":29\">{{Cite news|url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article198916311|title=Open Column.|date=1877-11-03|work=Tasmanian (Launceston, Tas. : 1871 - 1879)|access-date=2019-10-14|pages=6}}</ref> Some of those working to cancel the THIC's lease were Tasmanian politicians.<ref name=\":0\" />The THIC's view was that its holding the mineral lease for iron was not a barrier to gold mining, as it had consented to gold mining on its leasehold previously.<ref name=\":29\" />\n\nIn the face of increasing opposition\u2014and even parochial hostility\u2014to the THIC's mineral leases being held by [[Victoria (Australia)|Victorians]]<ref name=\":29\" />\u2014and with some perceived risk that those mineral leases might soon be cancelled, without compensation\u2014the THIC's Victorian shareholders finally gave up. In October 1877, the THIC resolved to dispose of its land and assets, with the stated hope that local Tasmanian capitalists might both resume the iron-making operation and work the gold.<ref name=\":29\" /> At the start of November 1877, the leases and assets were put up for sale.<ref name=\":30\" />  \n\nThe effective end of the THIC came on 10 December 1877, when the leases and other assets were sold to new owners.<ref name=\":19\" /> \n\n== Technology ==\n\n=== Process and equipment ===\n==== Blast furnace ====\nNo picture survives of the THIC blast furnace, but it was a small furnace that was similar in external appearance to the one at the Derwent Iron Company in Hobart.<ref name=\":9\">{{Cite news|url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article198922927|title=TAMAR HEMATITE IRON COMPANY.|date=1874-10-31|work=Tasmanian (Launceston, Tas. : 1871 - 1879)|access-date=2019-10-12|pages=6}}</ref><ref name=\":11\">{{Cite book|title=An iron will : mining at Beaconsfield - 1804 to 1877|last=Burch, Nigel|publisher=|year=|isbn=9780987371362|edition=  3rd|location=[Beaconsfield, Tasmania]|pages=193, 194, 195|oclc=1048604685}}</ref> The furnace was erected by Messrs Shields, of Hobart.<ref name=\":9\" />It was a \"Swedish\" cold-blast type, which used [[charcoal]] as its fuel and reducing agent. [[Limestone]] was used as a flux. \n\nThe furnace was designed to produce 20 to 25 tons of iron per week.<ref name=\":9\" /><ref name=\":11\" />It had the smallest capacity of the colonial-era blast furnaces that entered commercial production\u2014 a furnace of twelve times that capacity was used by the [[British and Tasmanian Charcoal Iron Company#Technology|British and Tasmanian Charcoal Iron Company]] and even the revived [[Fitzroy Iron Works]] furnace had five times the production capacity\u2014something that constrained the economic viability of the THIC operations, once iron prices fell from their peak of 1873. It seems that it was the company's intention\u2014having commenced operation and proven viability\u2014to seek more capital for a larger smelting operation.<ref name=\":31\" />\n\nThe blast furnace was constructed of [[Freestone (masonry)|freestone]]\u2014quarried on-site\u2014and bricks made from clay nearby, with a lining of imported English fire-bricks.<ref name=\":9\" /> <ref name=\":11\" />\"''The whole is substantially built, well bound together with strong hoops, arid the base firmly cramped, together.''\"<ref name=\":9\" /> It had three tuyeres, one on each side and one at the back.<ref name=\":9\" /><ref name=\":11\" />\n\nThe blast engine was a 16-horsepower (or 20-horsepower) horizontal-cylinder high-pressure (45-[[Pounds per square inch|psi]]) steam engine that powered two vertical blowing-cylinders\u2014of 30-inch diameter and 3-foot stroke\u2014via intermediate gearing from the shaft of the steam engine.<ref name=\":9\" /><ref name=\":11\" /> It was made by John Moore & Company, of Manchester<ref name=\":11\" /> and erected by Archibald and Jackson of Launceston.\n\n==== Charcoal kilns ====\nThere were two large charcoal kilns, each capable of turning out 1200 to 1500 [[Bushel|bushels]] of charcoal, over a period of three or four days and nights. <ref name=\":9\" />These were located alongside the tramway. There was a large charcoal storage shed near the blast furnace. <ref name=\":13\" />\n\nThe kilns were 10-feet wide by 50-feet long, and were constructed of slabs stuck on end into the ground. At one end the walls were 4-foot high, and gradually rose to 8-feet or 9-feet at the other end. Air-vents or \"nostril holes\" are formed in the sides 4-feet apart, by the insertion of earthen drain pipes. The inside walls were formed of sods, and then the kiln was filled with locally-cut wood, the top was covered with sods, and then fired. <ref name=\":9\" />\n\n=== Product quality ===\nThe pig-iron produced by the THIC's blast furnace was good quality and made good castings.<ref name=\":5\" /> THIC iron won first prize in its class at the [[Victorian Intercolonial Exhibition|Victorian Intercolonial Exhibition of 1875]].<ref name=\":26\" /><ref>{{Cite news|url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article72524632|title=THE INTERCOLONIAL EXHIBITION.|date=1875-09-20|work=Cornwall Chronicle (Launceston, Tas. : 1835 - 1880)|access-date=2019-10-14|pages=3}}</ref>\n\nAn analysis of the THIC pig-iron in England provided the results in the table below.<ref name=\":8\" />These results indicate a high quality pig-iron for its time, which\u2014except for the sulphur content\u2014would meet modern standards.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.metallics.org/pig-iron.html|title=Pig Iron|last=International Iron Metallics Association|date=2018-03-07|website=www.metallics.org|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2019-10-11}}</ref>\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|+THIC pig-iron analysis<ref name=\":8\" />\n|Iron\n|94.40%\n|-\n|Combined Carbon       \n|0.96%\n|-\n|Graphite (Carbon)\n|3.08%\n|-\n|Silicon\n|0.89%\n|-\n|Sulphur\n|0.22%\n|-\n|Phosphorus\n|0.09%\n|-\n|Manganese\n|0.24%\n|-\n|Loss\n|0.12%\n|-\n|'''Total'''\n|'''100.00%'''\n|}\n=== Transport ===\n\n==== Tramway ====\nThe tramway from the mine to Swifte's Jetty\u2014the site of the jetty, township and blast furnace\u2014was 1\u00be miles long. It ran though gently sloping country and required only three culverts to be constructed.<ref name=\":10\">{{Cite news|url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article52889765|title=Advertising|date=1873-11-18|work=Launceston Examiner (Tas. : 1842 - 1899)|access-date=2019-10-11|pages=6}}</ref><ref name=\":9\" /> At the blast furnace end, the tramway ran level right to the charging platform at the furnace top. There are two short branch tramways, one leading to the brick kiln and the other to the jetty.<ref name=\":13\" />\n\nThe tramway was horse-drawn. The gauge was 3-feet<ref name=\":9\" /> and the wooden rails were 4-inch by 4-inch hardwood timber.<ref name=\":10\" /><ref name=\":9\" /> Some of the wheels for the tramway trucks were cast from THIC pig-iron.<ref name=\":5\" />\n\n==== Jetty and shipping ====\nA timber jetty was erected on Middle Arm close to the site of the blast furnace. Materials and equipment was landed there during construction of other parts of the plant and the nearby township.\n\nThe water in the part of Middle Arm near the site of Swifte's Jetty is shallow and the bottom is exposed at low tide. [[Lighter (barge)|Lighters]] were used to carry the pig-iron to ships anchored in deeper water.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article8936524|title=THE MERCURY.|date=1875-04-13|work=Mercury (Hobart, Tas. : 1860 - 1954)|access-date=2019-10-13|pages=2}}</ref>Most of the iron was shipped to Melbourne, but some was shipped to England.\n\n== After iron ==\n\n=== Discovery of gold ===\nAfter iron mining on the THIC lease had ceased in mid-1875, the focus of mining interest around Brandy Creek\u2014now known as Beaconsfield\u2014became quartz-reef gold. The first of the significant quartz-reef gold mining companies, The Brandy Creek Quartz Gold Mining Company was established in December 1876. This company displaced some existing alluvial miners from its lease, and those miners moved to prospect in nearby areas.<ref>{{Cite book|title=An iron will : mining at Beaconsfield - 1804 to 1877|last=Burch, Nigel|publisher=|year=|isbn=9780987371362|edition=   3rd|location=[Beaconsfield, Tasmania]|pages=91|oclc=1048604685}}</ref>\n\nSome gold miners who held valid [[Miner's Right|Miner's Rights]] squatted on THIC lease\u2014with the expectation that the lease would be thrown open as a part of the surrounding goldfield<ref name=\":15\">{{Cite news|url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article233679936|title=Mining.|date=1878-03-16|work=Weekly Examiner (Launceston, Tas. : 1872 - 1878)|access-date=2019-10-12|pages=10}}</ref>\u2014and started to mine alluvial gold.<ref name=\":2\" />  Under the prevailing legislation, the THIC held the large lease only for the purpose of mining the iron ore and had no right to any gold found there, which  was legally the property of [[the Crown]].<ref name=\":3\" /> Some alluvial miners found payable amounts of gold on the THIC leasehold lands,<ref name=\":28\">{{Cite news|url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article233677155|title=GOLD NEWS|date=1877-09-15|work=Weekly Examiner (Launceston, Tas. : 1872 - 1878)|access-date=2019-10-14|pages=5}}</ref><ref name=\":7\" /> and some pegged claims.<ref name=\":28\" /><ref name=\":15\" />The dormant THIC did not interfere in any way with these small-scale gold mining operations; the company later claimed to have provided its consent to work gold on its lease to those whom had asked for it.<ref name=\":29\" />\n\nIn July 1877, the cap of a payable gold reef\u2014later known as the Tasmania Reef\u2014was discovered on the eastern slope of Cabbage Tree Hill, by brothers William and David Dally.<ref name=\":1\" /> Their claim was on [[Crown land#Australia|Crown land]], immediately adjacent to part of the THIC lease.\n\n=== Sale and new owners ===\nIt appears that at some point, the assets of the THIC were transferred to two of its major shareholders, Melbourne-based investors Hastings Cuningham and John Benn, in whose name the leaseholds were held. It was these two who subsequently put the assets and lease up for sale.<ref name=\":14\">{{Cite news|url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article233683493|title=THE HEMATITE IRON COMPANY.|date=1878-11-09|work=Weekly Examiner (Launceston, Tas. : 1872 - 1878)|access-date=2019-10-12|pages=20}}</ref> The assets and mineral lease of the THIC were originally advertised for a sale by auction on 22 November 1877,<ref name=\":30\">{{Cite news|url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article5943710|title=Advertising|date=1877-11-03|work=Argus (Melbourne, Vic. : 1848 - 1957)|access-date=2019-10-11|pages=10}}</ref> but the sale was deferred\u2014possibly twice<ref name=\":15\" />\u2014until 10 December 1877.<ref name=\":19\" />\n\nThe successful bidder was [[Adye Douglas|Ayde Douglas]]\u2014a prominent Tasmanian politician\u2014with a bid of just \u00a31,700.<ref name=\":19\">{{Cite news|url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article66068611|title=IRON.|date=1877-12-24|work=Cornwall Chronicle (Launceston, Tas. : 1835 - 1880)|access-date=2019-10-11|pages=6}}</ref> He was just one of the new owners. The others were three weathy Tasmanian politicians\u2014[[William Dawson Grubb]], [[William Hart (politician)|William Hart]], [[Members of the Tasmanian House of Assembly, 1872\u20131877|Samuel Tulloch]]\u2014and a Launceston merchant, John Murphy. All these other new owners had recently had dealings\u2014relevant to the THIC\u2014that were associated with gold mining; perhaps that was why it was Ayde Douglas\u2014an investor in the rival Ilfracombe Iron Company<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article52888782|title=OUR IRON MINES.|date=1873-09-20|work=Launceston Examiner (Tas. : 1842 - 1899)|access-date=2019-10-14|pages=5}}</ref> and later the buyer of its dormant assets<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article8929438|title=OUR LAUNCESTON LETTER.|date=1874-04-18|work=Mercury (Hobart, Tas. : 1860 - 1954)|access-date=2019-10-14|pages=3}}</ref>\u2014who bid for the THIC lands and assets.\n\nHart, Tulloch and Murphy had, as recently as October 1877, been attempting to have the THIC mineral lease cancelled but had failed.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite news|url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article37151635|title=GOLD NEWS.|date=1877-10-11|work=Launceston Examiner (Tas. : 1842 - 1899)|access-date=2019-10-10|pages=2}}</ref>\n\nGrubb and Hart had bought the Tasmania Reef claim from the Dally brothers, in October 1877, for \u00a35,000 and a tenth share of any company formed to mine the quartz reef.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article198916577|title=GOLD.|date=1877-10-13|work=Tasmanian (Launceston, Tas. : 1871 - 1879)|access-date=2019-10-10|pages=9}}</ref>The THIC leasehold adjoined the Tasmania Reef claim<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article895824|title=The Brisbane Courier.|date=1879-12-08|work=Brisbane Courier (Qld. : 1864 - 1933)|access-date=2019-10-11|pages=2}}</ref> but the full significance of that proximity was not apparent, at the time that Douglas acquired the THIC assets so cheaply.\n\nAlthough the sale of the lease and assets was the effective end of the Tamar Hematite Iron Company, the collective interest of new owners continued to be known as 'the Hematite Company' for some years later.<ref name=\":7\" /><ref name=\":14\" /> Their new property comprised \"''over 700 acres of freehold, leasehold, and other land, with buildings, machinery, and other property''\".<ref name=\":19\" />\n\n=== Mineral Lands Act of 1877 and dispute with gold miners ===\nOn 14 December 1877, Grubb and Hart visited the old THIC lease and gave the alluvial gold miners already working on the lease a notice to quit. This came about unexpectedly; the THIC mineral lease did not give the THIC right to mine gold and, previously,  the THIC had  consented to gold mining on its lease. It soon became known that the new owners' intransigent position was based on an interpretation of a newly-passed piece of legislation, the Mineral Lands Act of 1877.<ref name=\":2\">{{Cite news|url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article66068609|title=OUR GOLD MINES.|date=1877-12-24|work=Cornwall Chronicle (Launceston, Tas. : 1835 - 1880)|access-date=2019-10-10|pages=6}}</ref><ref name=\":3\">{{Cite news|url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article198917724|title=BRANDY CREEK GOLD FIELDS. WEST TAMAR.|date=1877-12-22|work=Tasmanian (Launceston, Tas. : 1871 - 1879)|access-date=2019-10-10|pages=4}}</ref><ref name=\":15\" />  \n\nThe Waste Lands Act 1863, first made provision for mineral leases for terms not exceeding twenty-one years, on any waste lands.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://eprints.utas.edu.au/22425/1/Whole-Meikle-thesis.pdf|title=Cronyism, Muddle and Money: Land Allocation in Tasmania under the Waste Lands Acts, 1856-1889|last=Meikle|first=Bronwyn|date=August 2014|website=|page=241|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> The THIC's lease for its leasehold land  was made under a later act, The Mineral Leases Act, 1870, which only gave the THIC a right to mine the iron ore, and not gold.<ref name=\":0\" /> Gold mining was subject to a separate Act, The Gold Fields Regulation Act, 1870.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://classic.austlii.edu.au/au/legis/tas/num_act/tgra187034vn6304/|title=The Goldfields Regulation Act, 1870 (34 Vic, No 6)|website=classic.austlii.edu.au|access-date=2019-10-10}}</ref> \n\nHowever, one day after the sale of the THIC lease and assets, the Mineral Lands Act of 1877, had come into force. Clause 30 of the new act effectively gave the holder of an existing mineral lease a [[Pre-emption right|pre-emptive right]] to take out a gold lease, if gold had been discovered on any part of the same land.<ref name=\":18\">{{Cite news|url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article233678570|title=THE MINERAL LANDS ACT|date=1877-12-22|work=Weekly Examiner (Launceston, Tas. : 1872 - 1878)|access-date=2019-10-12|pages=13}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.austlii.edu.au/cgi-bin/viewdoc/au/legis/tas/num_act/tmla187741vn7219/tmla187741vn7219.html|title=Mineral Lands Act, 1877|last=Tasmanian Parliamant|date=11 December 1877|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>It seems it was an unintended consequence of a clause intended to prevent alluvial tin miners failing to recover gold that was present on their tin-mining leases and to prevent such gold going to waste. However, it is possible that the tin-mining case was only a rationalisation, to justify a [[loophole]] that had been created\u2014perhaps deliberately\u2014in the legislation. \n\nAfter buying the mineral lease, the new owners immediately paid the arrears rent for the lease (\u00a3310) and then\u2014as a lessee in good standing until 31 December 1877\u2014pegged a gold mining claim,<ref name=\":15\" />under The Gold Fields Regulation Act. According to the Goldfield Regulation Act, a gold mining claim needed to be on public display for a period of 30-days, but the new owners had back-dated their claim, allowing no time for an objection to be raised.<ref name=\":162\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.qvmag.tas.gov.au/files/assets/qvmag/library/.../tamar-valley-industrial.pdf|title=TAMAR VALLEY INDUSTRIAL HERITAGE \u2013 a survey|last=Morris-Nunn|first=Miranda|last2=Tassel|first2=C. B.|date=1984|website=|publisher=Queen Victoria Museum|pages=63|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>  \n\nOvernight, the price paid for the leased land and other THIC assets by the new owners\u2014mainly wealthy Tasmanian politicians\u2014became a remarkable bargain. The buyers' cronyism, connivance, and conflict of interest\u2014as politicians who had recently debated and voted upon the new Act\u2014seemed obvious,<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article198917724|title=BRANDY CREEK GOLD FIELDS. WEST TAMAR.|date=1877-12-22|work=Tasmanian (Launceston, Tas. : 1871 - 1879)|access-date=2019-10-11|pages=4}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article201724526|title=No title|date=1879-03-27|work=Tribune (Hobart, Tas. : 1876 - 1879)|access-date=2019-10-10|pages=2}}</ref> but their actions had been completely legal.<ref>{{Cite book|title=An iron will : mining at Beaconsfield - 1804 to 1877|last=Burch, Nigel|publisher=|year=|isbn=9780987371362|edition=   3rd|location=[Beaconsfield, Tasmania]|pages=240\u2013243|oclc=1048604685}}</ref> \n\nThe new arrangements were controversial<ref name=\":18\" />; there was disputation, during 1878 and 1879, between the new owners\u2014collectively known as 'the Hematite Company'\u2014and the small-scale gold miners,<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article66504118|title=MINING NOTES.|date=1879-03-07|work=Cornwall Chronicle (Launceston, Tas. : 1835 - 1880)|access-date=2019-10-12|pages=2}}</ref> and protests from others concerned about the probity of the way the new owners had acquired the gold rights.<ref name=\":15\" /><ref name=\":14\" /><ref name=\":18\" /> \n\n=== Quartz reef mining on the 'Hematite Company' lease ===\nBy October 1878, it had become well known that the rich Tasmania Reef extended onto the old THIC  leasehold land. A new company, The Tasmania Extended Gold Mining Company was set up to mine gold, on ten acres of land on Cabbage Tree Hill, due east of the Tasmanian Mine lease and to the south of two other gold leases. The land included a part of the bounteous Tasmania Reef, which could be accessed by extending the workings of the Tasmania Mine over the boundary of the 'Hematite Company' lease. The 'Hematite Company' interests received a small number of shares in the new company, but received a lucrative 5% royalty on the gold mined.<ref name=\":7\">{{Cite news|url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article66501753|title=Advertising|date=1878-10-29|work=Cornwall Chronicle (Launceston, Tas. : 1835 - 1880)|access-date=2019-10-11|pages=3}}</ref><ref name=\":14\" />\n\nThe Tasmania Mine had paid dividends of over \u00a3700,000 by 1900.<ref name=\"Saclier\">M. J. Saclier: [http://adb.anu.edu.au/biography/grubb-william-dawson-3676/text5743 ''Grubb, William Dawson (1817\u20131879)''], Australian Dictionary of Biography, National Centre of Biography, Australian National University, published first in hardcopy 1972, accessed online 16 January 2018.</ref>It was one of the deepest and richest mines in Australia, by the time it closed in 1914.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.beaconsfieldgold.com.au/CompanyProfile.html|title=History of Gold at Beaconsfield|work=Company Profile|publisher=Beaconsfield Gold NL|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://archive.is/20060511233844/http://www.beaconsfieldgold.com.au/CompanyProfile.html|archivedate=11 May 2006|accessdate=2006-05-09}}</ref>Although William Grubb died in 1879, his family\u2014benefiting from both his share of the Tasmania Mine and the 'Hematite Company' royalty\u2014became  even more weathly<ref name=\"Saclier\" /><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.australiancountry.com.au/updates/a-proud-family-home/|title=A PROUD FAMILY HOME|date=2016-12-12|website=Australian Country|language=en|access-date=2019-10-11}}</ref>, as did the other partners in 'the Hematite Company'.\n\n=== Iron ore deposit ===\nAlthough the underground quartz reef workings would not affect the surface quarrying of iron ore, the surface workings were also soon thrown open to gold mining. The 'Hematite Company' agreed, in March 1879, to allow alluvial miners to work parts of the old lease.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article201726673|title=No title|date=1879-03-28|work=Tribune (Hobart, Tas. : 1876 - 1879)|access-date=2019-10-12|pages=2}}</ref> ; their decision to accept this compromise outcome foreshadowed an amendment made, in November 1880, to the legislation.<ref name=\":20\">{{Cite news|url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article38264661|title=LAUNCESTON EXAMINER.|date=1880-11-20|work=Launceston Examiner (Tas. : 1842 - 1899)|access-date=2019-10-12|pages=2}}</ref>\n\nThe THIC lease's iron ore was not used again,<ref name=\":6\" />apart from during 1890-1892, when 1,000 tons of ore were shipped to Melbourne for [[History of manufactured fuel gases#Appliances and machinery of the historic gas-works|town gas purification]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.mrt.tas.gov.au/mrtdoc/dominfo/download/OS_204/OS_204.pdf|title=REPORT ON THE MINERAL RESOURCES OF THE BEACONSFIELD AND SALISURY DISTRICTS|last=Twelvetrees|first=W.H.|date=13 March 1903|website=|publisher=Government Geologist's Office, Launceston|page=6, 7|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref><ref name=\":23\" />\n\n=== Other ex-THIC assets ===\nSwifte's Jetty was replaced in 1879<ref name=\":24\" /> and the replacement jetty was used to land gold mining equipment,<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article38262613|title=MINING INTELLIGENCE.|last=|first=|date=1880-09-16|work=Launceston Examiner (Tas. : 1842 - 1899)|access-date=2019-10-11|pages=2}}</ref> Presumably, the tramway that conveniently ran east-west from the jetty to near the gold mines stayed in use for a while too. \n\nThe blast furnace was still standing in 1883, when the government geologist, Gustav Thureau, collected samples of THIC iron from its hearth.<ref name=\":210\">{{Cite book|title=An iron will : mining at Beaconsfield - 1804 to 1877|last=Burch, Nigel|publisher=|year=|isbn=9780987371362|edition= 3rd|location=[Beaconsfield, Tasmania]|pages=181, 182|oclc=1048604685}}</ref> Its blast engine and blowing cylinders were still there in November 1883; this is known because Alfred Ritchie was later charged with stealing two engine cylinders to sell as scrap iron. The cylinders had been broken up, before being sold to a foundry in Launceston.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article199529545|title=GEORGE TOWN POLICE COURT|date=1884-06-14|work=Tasmanian (Launceston, Tas. : 1881 - 1895)|access-date=2019-10-12|pages=22}}</ref> \n\n== Legacy and remnants ==\nThe Mineral Lands Act of 1877 was amended in November 1880. The new act repealed Clause 30 of the 1877 Act,<ref name=\":20\" /><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://classic.austlii.edu.au/au/legis/tas/num_act/tmlaa188044vn17299/tmlaa188044vn17299.pdf|title=An Act to amend the Mineral Lands Act of 1877|last=Tasmanian Government|date=1 November 1880|website=1877 Tasmanian Numbered Acts - AustLII|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> under which the buyers of the THIC assets had craftily acquired a fortune in gold, at the small cost of \u00a31,700 and \u00a3310 in arrears rent.\n\nThe jetty and the township at Swifte's Jetty on the Middle Arm of the Tamar River estuary\u2014at the locality now known as Scotchman's Point\u2014are now long gone. Any remains of the blast furnace were buried under gold mine tailings that were reprocessed during the 1980s.<ref name=\":4\">{{Cite book|title=An iron will : mining at Beaconsfield - 1804 to 1877|last=Burch, Nigel|publisher=|year=|isbn=9780987371362|edition=   3rd|location=[Beaconsfield, Tasmania]|pages=243|oclc=1048604685}}</ref> The area where the old town and iron plant stood was still known as \"Swift's ''[sic]'' Jetty\"  well into the 20th-Century,<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article91417141|title=BEACONSFIELD COUNCIL|date=1944-10-17|work=Examiner (Launceston, Tas. : 1900 - 1954)|access-date=2019-10-12|pages=3}}</ref> but is no longer known by that name. Algernon Swifte himself is largely forgotten.<ref name=\":24\">{{Cite book|title=An iron will : mining at Beaconsfield - 1804 to 1877|last=Burch, Nigel|publisher=|year=|isbn=9780987371362|edition=  3rd|location=[Beaconsfield, Tasmania]|pages=243|oclc=1048604685}}</ref> \n\nThe site of the THIC iron ore mine, near Brandy Creek slightly north-west of the modern-day town of Beaconsfield, is now reserved as a source of gravel; iron ore still outcrops at the site.<ref name=\":6\">{{Cite book|title=An iron will : mining at Beaconsfield - 1804 to 1877|last=Burch, Nigel|publisher=|year=|isbn=9780987371362|edition=  3rd|location=[Beaconsfield, Tasmania]|pages=196|oclc=1048604685}}</ref>Although it still contains iron ore, the ore deposit is far too small and not rich enough to be commercially viable today. \n\nA part of the cast iron fence of the Pilgrim [[Uniting Church in Australia|Uniting Church]]\u2014built as a [[Wesleyan theology|Wesleyan]] Church\u2014in Paterson St, Launceston is made from pig-iron made by the THIC. The fencing was among the castings made at the foundry of William Peters, in Wellington St, Launceston, in late April 1875.<ref>{{Cite book|title=An iron will : mining at Beaconsfield - 1804 to 1877|last=Burch, Nigel|publisher=|year=|isbn=9780987371362|edition=   3rd|location=[Beaconsfield, Tasmania]|pages=204, 205|oclc=1048604685}}</ref><ref name=\":5\">{{Cite news|url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article8936968|title=OUR LAUNCESTON LETTER.|date=1875-05-01|work=Mercury (Hobart, Tas. : 1860 - 1954)|access-date=2019-10-10|pages=2}}</ref>\n\n== See also ==\n\n* [[British and Tasmanian Charcoal Iron Company]] \n*[[Ilfracombe Iron Company]]\n*[[Beaconsfield, Tasmania]]\n\n== References ==\n<!--- See [[Wikipedia:Footnotes]] on how to create references using <ref></ref> tags which will then appear here automatically -->\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n<!-- Use the format: * [http://www.example.com/ example.com] -->\n\n<!--- Categories --->*[http://classic.austlii.edu.au/au/legis/tas/num_act/tmla187034vn11229/ <nowiki>Mineral Leases Act of 1870 [18 October, 1870]</nowiki>]\n*[http://www.austlii.edu.au/cgi-bin/viewdoc/au/legis/tas/num_act/tmla187741vn7219/tmla187741vn7219.html <nowiki>The Mineral Lands Act of 1877 [11 December 1877]</nowiki>]\n*[http://classic.austlii.edu.au/au/legis/tas/num_act/tmlaa188044vn17299/tmlaa188044vn17299.pdf <nowiki>An Act to amend \"The Mineral Lands Act of 1877\" [1 November 1880]</nowiki>]\n*[http://www.mrt.tas.gov.au/mrtdoc/dominfo/download/OS_204/OS_204.pdf \"Report on the Mineral Resources of the Districts of Beaconsfield and Salisbury\", W.H.Twelvetrees, Government Geologist's Office, Launceston 13 March 1903]\n*[http://www.mrt.tas.gov.au/mrtdoc/dominfo/download/GSMR06/GSMR06.pdf \"The Iron Ore Deposits of Tasmania\", W.H.Twelvetrees and A.M.Reid, Tasmania Department of Mines (1919)]\n\n<br />\n\n{{coord missing|Tasmania}}\n\n[[Category:Iron mining in Australia]]\n[[Category:Mines in Tasmania]]\n[[Category:1874 establishments in Australia]]\n", "name_user": "LilHelpa", "label": "safe", "comment": "typo; mnr copy edit", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Tamar_Hematite_Iron_Company"}
{"title_page": "Deputy Prime Minister of Romania", "text_new": "{{Refimprove|date=March 2020}}\n{{Infobox official post\n|post            = Deputy Prime Minister\n|body            = Romania\n|native_name     = {{small|''Vice prim ministru Guvernului Rom\u00e2niei''}}\n|image           = File:Conventia_PD-L_2013_-_Raluca_Turcan_(cropped).jpg\n|incumbent       = [[Raluca Turcan]]\n|incumbentsince  = 4 November 2019\n|appointer       = [[Prime Minister of Romania]]\n|formation       = \n|inaugural       = \n|website         = {{URL|gov.ro}}\n}}\n{{Politics of Romania}}\n\nThe '''Deputy Prime Minister of Romania''' ({{lang-ro|Vice prim ministru Guvernului Rom\u00e2niei}}) is a minister in the [[Government of Romania]]. It is considered a [[Minister without portfolio|non-portfolio]] role.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.romania-insider.com/romania-new-ministers-orban-government|title=Who are the 16 ministers in Romanian PM Ludovic Orban's team?|date=4 November 2019|work=Romania Insider|access-date=2 February 2020}}</ref>\n\n== List of Deputy Prime Ministers (1980\u2013present) ==\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align:center\"\n! colspan=1 | Portrait\n! Name\n! colspan=2 | Term of office\n! Party\n! colspan=1 | Prime Minister\n|-\n| [[File:Elena_Ceausescu_portrait.jpg|75px]]\n| [[Elena Ceau\u0219escu]]\n| 29 March 1980\n| 22 December 1989\n| [[Romanian Communist Party|PCR]]\n| [[Ilie Verde\u021b]]<br />[[Constantin D\u0103sc\u0103lescu]]\n|-\n| [[File:No_image.svg|75px]]\n| Gelu Voican Voiculescu\n| 26 December 1989\n| 28 June 1990\n| [[National Salvation Front (Romania)|FSN]]\n| [[Petre Roman]]\n|-\n| [[File:No_image.svg|75px]]\n| [[Mihai Dr\u0103g\u0103nescu]]\n| 26 December 1989\n| 28 June 1990\n| [[National Salvation Front (Romania)|FSN]]\n| [[Petre Roman]]\n|-\n| [[File:No_image.svg|75px]]\n| Ion Aurel Stoica\n| 26 December 1989\n| 28 June 1990\n| [[National Salvation Front (Romania)|FSN]]\n| [[Petre Roman]]\n|-\n| [[File:No_image.svg|75px]]\n| Anton V\u0103t\u0103\u0219escu\n| 26 December 1989\n| 28 June 1990\n| [[National Salvation Front (Romania)|FSN]]\n| [[Petre Roman]]\n|-\n| colspan=2 {{CNone|''Office not in use''}}\n| colspan=2 {{CNone|1990\u20132008}}\n| colspan=2 {{n/a}}\n|-\n| [[File:Dan_Nica_reuniunea_BPN_a_PSD_-_06.01.2014_(cropped).jpg|75px]]\n| [[Dan Nica]]\n| 22 December 2008\n| 1 October 2009\n| [[Social Democratic Party (Romania)|PSD]]\n| [[Emil Boc]]\n|-\n| [[File:Conventia PD-L 2013 - Vasile Blaga (2) (cropped).jpg|75px]]\n| [[Vasile Blaga]]<br />(Acting)\n| 1 October 2009\n| 27 November 2009\n| [[Democratic Liberal Party (Romania)|PDL]]\n| [[Emil Boc]]\n|-\n| [[File:B\u00e9la Mark\u00f3 2010-06-05.jpg|75px]]\n| [[B\u00e9la Mark\u00f3]]\n| 23 December 2009\n| 9 February 2012\n| [[Democratic Alliance of Hungarians in Romania|UDMR]]\n| [[Emil Boc]]\n|-\n| colspan=2 {{CNone|''Office not in use''}}\n| colspan=2 {{CNone|2012}}\n| colspan=2 {{n/a}}\n|-\n| [[File:No_image.svg|75px]]\n| Florin Georgescu\n| 7 May 2012\n| 21 December 2012\n| Independent\n| [[Victor Ponta]]\n|-\n| [[File:Victor Ponta la semnarea declaratiei politice privind infiintarea USL 2.0 - 14.11 (3) (15621867427) (cropped).jpg|75px]]\n| [[Liviu Dragnea]]\n| 21 December 2012\n| 13 December 2014\n| [[Social Democratic Party (Romania)|PSD]]\n| [[Victor Ponta]]\n|-\n| [[File:No_image.svg|75px]]\n| [[Daniel Chi\u021boiu]]\n| 21 December 2012\n| 19 February 2014\n| [[National Liberal Party (Romania)|PNL]]\n| [[Victor Ponta]]\n|-\n| [[File:Gabriel Oprea 2011-10-20.jpg|75px]]\n| [[Gabriel Oprea]]\n| 21 December 2012\n| 9 November 2015\n| [[National Union for the Progress of Romania|UNPR]]\n| [[Victor Ponta]]\n|-\n| [[File:Victor Ponta Feb 2014 (cropped 2).jpg|75px]]\n| [[Victor Ponta]]<br />(Acting)\n| 19 February 2014\n| 5 March 2014\n| [[Social Democratic Party (Romania)|PSD]]\n| Himself\n|-\n| [[File:Daniel_Constantin.jpg|75px]]\n| [[Daniel Constantin (politician)|Daniel Constantin]]\n| 5 March 2014\n| 13 December 2014\n| [[Conservative Party (Romania)|PC]]\n| [[Victor Ponta]]\n|-\n| [[File:Kelemen Hunor.jpg|75px]]\n| [[Hunor Kelemen]]\n| 5 March 2014\n| 24 November 2014\n| [[Democratic Alliance of Hungarians in Romania|UDMR]]\n| [[Victor Ponta]]\n|-\n| [[File:Csilla Heged\u00fcs.jpg|75px]]\n| [[Csilla Heged\u00fcs]]\n| 24 November 2014\n| 13 December 2014\n| [[Democratic Alliance of Hungarians in Romania|UDMR]]\n| [[Victor Ponta]]\n|-\n| [[File:No_image.svg|75px]]\n| [[Vasile D\u00eencu]]\n| 17 November 2015\n| 4 January 2017\n| Independent\n| [[Dacian Ciolo\u0219]]\n|-\n| [[File:No_image.svg|75px]]\n| [[Costin Borc]]\n| 17 November 2015\n| 4 January 2017\n| Independent\n| [[Dacian Ciolo\u0219]]\n|-\n| [[File:Sevil-Shhaideh-2015_(cropped).JPG|75px]]\n| [[Sevil Shhaideh]]\n| 4 January 2017\n| 16 June 2017\n| [[Social Democratic Party (Romania)|PSD]]\n| [[Sorin Grindeanu]]\n|-\n| [[File:No_image.svg|75px]]\n| Augustin Jianu\n| 16 June 2017\n| 29 June 2017\n| [[Social Democratic Party (Romania)|PSD]]\n| [[Sorin Grindeanu]]\n|-\n| [[File:Sevil-Shhaideh-2015_(cropped).JPG|75px]]\n| [[Sevil Shhaideh]]\n| 29 June 2017\n| 17 October 2017\n| [[Social Democratic Party (Romania)|PSD]]\n| [[Mihai Tudose]]\n|-\n| [[File:No_image.svg|75px]]\n| [[Paul St\u0103nescu]]\n| 17 October 2017\n| 4 November 2019\n| [[Social Democratic Party (Romania)|PSD]]\n| [[Mihai Tudose]]<br />[[Viorica D\u0103ncil\u0103]]\n|-\n| [[File:Conventia PD-L 2013 - Raluca Turcan (cropped).jpg|75px]]\n| [[Raluca Turcan]]\n| 4 November 2019\n| ''Incumbent''\n| [[National Liberal Party (Romania)|PNL]]\n| [[Ludovic Orban]]\n|-\n|}\n\n== See also ==\n*[[List of Prime Ministers of Romania]]\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n[[Category:1980 establishments in Romania]]\n[[Category:Deputy prime ministers]]\n", "text_old": "{{Refimprove|date=March 2020}}\n{{Infobox official post\n|post            = Deputy Prime Minister\n|body            = Romania\n|native_name     = {{small|''Vice prim ministru Guvernului Rom\u00e2niei''}}\n|image           = File:Conventia_PD-L_2013_-_Raluca_Turcan_(cropped).jpg\n|incumbent       = [[Raluca Turcan]]\n|incumbentsince  = 4 November 2019\n|appointer       = [[Prime Minister of Romania]]\n|formation       = \n|inaugural       = \n|website         = {{URL|gov.ro}}\n}}\n{{Politics of Romania}}\n\nThe '''Deputy Prime Minister of Romania''' ({{lang-ro|Vice prim ministru Guvernului Rom\u00e2niei}}) is a minister in the [[Government of Romania]]. It is considered a [[Minister without portfolio|non-portfolio]] role.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.romania-insider.com/romania-new-ministers-orban-government|title=Who are the 16 ministers in Romanian PM Ludovic Orban's team?|date=4 November 2019|work=Romania Insider|access-date=2 February 2020}}</ref>\n\n== List of Deputy Prime Ministers (1980\u2013present) ==\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align:center\"\n! colspan=1 | Portrait\n! Name\n! colspan=2 | Term of office\n! Party\n! colspan=1 | Prime Minister\n|-\n| [[File:Elena_Ceausescu_portrait.jpg|75px]]\n| [[Elena Ceau\u0219escu]]\n| 29 March 1980\n| 22 December 1989\n| [[Romanian Communist Party|PCR]]\n| [[Ilie Verde\u021b]]<br />[[Constantin D\u0103sc\u0103lescu]]\n|-\n| [[File:No_image.svg|75px]]\n| Gelu Voican Voiculescu\n| 26 December 1989\n| 28 June 1990\n| [[National Salvation Front (Romania)|FSN]]\n| [[Petre Roman]]\n|-\n| [[File:No_image.svg|75px]]\n| [[Mihai Dr\u0103g\u0103nescu]]\n| 26 December 1989\n| 28 June 1990\n| [[National Salvation Front (Romania)|FSN]]\n| [[Petre Roman]]\n|-\n| [[File:No_image.svg|75px]]\n| Ion Aurel Stoica\n| 26 December 1989\n| 28 June 1990\n| [[National Salvation Front (Romania)|FSN]]\n| [[Petre Roman]]\n|-\n| [[File:No_image.svg|75px]]\n| Anton V\u0103t\u0103\u0219escu\n| 26 December 1989\n| 28 June 1990\n| [[National Salvation Front (Romania)|FSN]]\n| [[Petre Roman]]\n|-\n| colspan=2 {{CNone|''Office not in use''}}\n| colspan=2 {{CNone|1990\u20132008}}\n| colspan=2 {{n/a}}\n|-\n| [[File:Dan_Nica_reuniunea_BPN_a_PSD_-_06.01.2014_(cropped).jpg|75px]]\n| 